S"NOTE 1 &#150; SUMMARY OF SIGNIFICANT\rACCOUNTING POLICIES HISTORY ROKWADER, INC. (the Company), was organized\runder the laws of the State of Delaware on March 18, 2005 as a vehicle to seek, investigate and, if such investigation warrants,\racquire a target company or business that primarily desires to seek the perceived advantages of a publicly-held corporation. On\rApril 23, 2007, Rokwader completed an acquisition of all of the issued and outstanding capital stock of Latigo Shore Music, Inc.\r(&#147;Latigo&#148;). Substantially all of the business conducted by Rokwader is through Latigo, its wholly-owned subsidiary.\rIn May and June 2015, the Company underwent a change of control when it sold an aggregate of 15,250,000 shares of its common stock,\rtogether with a warrant to purchase an additional 5,900,000 shares of its common stock to Coco Partners, LLC. As a result of this\rtransaction and the change of control of the Company, our business strategies and plan of operations have evolved into two segments:\r(i) the continuation of the Latigo music publishing business; and (ii) the investment and acquisition vehicle through Coco Partners. BASIS OF CONSOLIDATION The consolidated financial statements\rinclude the accounts of Rokwader, Inc. and subsidiary. Inter-Company accounts and transactions have been eliminated. INCOME TAXES The Company follows the guidance of\rthe Financial Accounting Standards Board&#146;s Accounting Standards Codification Topic 740 related to Income Taxes. According\rto Topic 740, deferred income taxes are recorded to reflect the tax consequences in future years of temporary differences between\rthe tax basis of the assets and liabilities and their financial amounts at year-end. For federal income tax purposes, substantially\rall expenses incurred prior to the commencement of operations must be deferred and then they may be written off over a 180-month\rperiod. Tax deductible losses can be carried forward for 20 years until utilized for federal tax purposes. The Company will provide\ra valuation allowance in the full amount of the deferred tax assets since there is no assurance of future taxable income. Additionally,\rthe Company may reserve a portion of the deferred tax assets due to restrictions of tax benefits related to changes in ownership. The Company utilizes the Financial Accounting\rStandards Board&#146;s Accounting Standards Codification Topic 740 related to Income Taxes to account for the uncertainty in income\rtaxes. Topic 740 for Income Taxes clarifies the accounting for uncertainty in income taxes by prescribing rules for recognition,\rmeasurement and classification in financial statements of tax positions taken or expected to be in a tax return. Further, it prescribes\ra two-step process for the financial statement measurement and recognition of a tax position. The first step involves the determination\rof whether it is more likely than not (greater than 50 percent likelihood) that a tax position will be sustained upon examination,\rbased on the technical merits of the position. The second step requires that any tax position that meets the more likely than not\rrecognition threshold be measured and recognized in the financial statements at the largest amount of benefit that is a greater\rthan 50 percent likelihood of being realized upon ultimate settlement. This topic also provides guidance on the accounting for\rrelated interest and penalties, financial statement classification and disclosure. The Company&#146;s policy is that any interest\ror penalties related to uncertain tax positions are recognized in income tax expense when incurred. The Company has no uncertain\rtax positions or related interest or penalties requiring accrual at December 31, 2015 and December 31, 2014. CASH AND CASH EQUIVALENTS Cash and cash equivalents consist primarily\rof cash in banks and highly liquid investments with original maturities of 90 days or less. CONCENTRATIONS OF CREDIT RISK The Company maintains all cash in deposit\raccounts, which at times may exceed federally insured limits. The Company has not experienced a loss in such accounts. As of December 31, 2015, the Company\rhad bank balances of $5,165,219 in two banks. The Company holds more than $250,000 in interest bearing accounts at one bank, thus\rthere is a credit risk related to these cash deposits as of December 31, 2015 of $4,849,763 since these amounts exceed the current\rfederally insured amount of $250,000 per depositor, per insured bank, for each account ownership category.   EARNINGS PER COMMON SHARE Basic earnings per common share are\rcomputed based upon the weighted average number of common shares outstanding during the period. Diluted earnings per share consists\rof the weighted average number of common shares outstanding plus the dilutive effects of options and warrants calculated using\rthe treasury stock method. In loss periods, dilutive common equivalent shares are excluded as the effect would be anti-dilutive. USE OF ESTIMATES IN THE PREPARATION\rOF FINANCIAL STATEMENTS The preparation of financial statements\rin conformity with generally accepted accounting principles requires management to make estimates and assumptions that affect the\rreported amounts of assets and liabilities, the disclosure of contingent assets and liabilities at the date of the financial statements\rand the reported amounts of revenues and expenses during the reporting periods. Actual results could differ from those estimates\rand assumptions. LONG-LIVED ASSETS The realizability of long-lived assets\ris evaluated periodically as events or circumstances indicate a possible inability to recover the carrying amount. Long-lived assets\rthat will no longer be used in our business are written-off in the period identified since they are no longer expected to generate\rany positive cash flows for us. Long-lived assets that continue to be used by us are periodically evaluated for recoverability.\rSuch evaluation is based on various analyses, including cash flow and profitability projections. The analyses necessarily involve\rsignificant management judgment. In the event the projected undiscounted cash flows are less than net book value of the assets,\rthe carrying value of the assets is written down to its estimated fair value. No impairment loss on intangible assets\rwas recognized for the years ended December 31, 2015 and 2014, respectively. REVENUE RECOGNITION As required by FASB ASC Topic 605, Revenue\rRecognition (&#147;ASC 605&#148;), the Company recognizes revenue when persuasive evidence of an arrangement exists, delivery\rhas occurred, the sales price is fixed or determinable and collection is probable.Revenues are earned from the receipt of royalties relating to the licensing of rights in musical compositions. The receipt of royalties\rprincipally relates to amounts earned from the public performance of copyrighted material, the mechanical reproduction of copyrighted\rmaterial on recorded media including digital formats, and the use of copyrighted material in synchronization with visual images.\rConsistent with industry practice, music publishing royalties generally are recognized as revenue when cash is received. Revenue\rgenerally is recognized net of any taxes collected from customers and subsequently remitted to governmental authorities. PROPERTY AND EQUIPMENT Property and equipment are stated at\rcost and are depreciated using the straight-line method over the estimated useful lives of the respective assets, which are as\rfollows: Equipment 2-10 yearsFurniture 2-10 years Expenditures for repairs and maintenance\rare charged to expense as incurred. The costs of major renewals and betterments are capitalized. The cost and related accumulated\rdepreciation of property and equipment are removed from the accounts upon retirement or other disposition and any resulting gain\ror loss is reflected in operations of the period.  RECENT ACCOUNTING PRONOUNCEMENTS In November 2015, the FASB issued ASU\r2015-17, Income Taxes (Topic 740) Balance Sheet Classification of Deferred Taxes. ASU 2015-17 requires that deferred tax liabilities\rand assets be classified as noncurrent in a classified statement of financial position. The amendments in this Update apply to\rall entities that present a classified statement of financial position. The current requirement that deferred tax liabilities and\rassets of a tax-paying component of an entity be offset and presented as a single amount is not affected by the amendments in this\rUpdate. The amendments in this Update will align the presentation of deferred income tax assets and liabilities with International\rFinancial Reporting Standards (IFRS). IAS 1, Presentation of Financial Statements, requires deferred tax assets and liabilities\rto be classified as noncurrent in a classified statement of financial position. For public entities, the amendments in ASU 2015-17\rwill be effective for financial statements issued for annual periods beginning after December 15, 2016 and interim periods within\rthose annual periods. For all other entities, thee amendments in this Update are effective for financial statements issued for\rannual periods beginning after December 15, 2017, and interim periods within annual periods beginning after December 15, 2018.\rEarlier application is permitted for all entities as of the beginning of an interim or annual reporting period. The amendments\rin this Update may be applied either prospectively to all deferred tax liabilities and assets or retrospectively to all periods\rpresented. If an entity applies the guidance prospectively, the entity should disclose in the first interim and first annual period\rof change, the nature of and reason for the change in accounting principle and a statement that prior periods were not retrospectively\radjusted. If an entity applies the guidance retrospectively, the entity should disclose in the first interim and first annual period\rof change the nature of and reason for the change in accounting principle and quantitative information about the effects of the\raccounting change on prior periods. The Company is currently assessing this guidance for future implementation. In February 2015, the FASB issued ASU\r2015-02, Consolidation (Topic 810) Amendments to the Consolidation Analysis. ASU 2015-02 change the analysis that a reporting entity\rmust perform to determine whether it should consolidate certain types of legal entities. The amendments in this Update affect the\rfollowing areas: (1) Limited partnerships and similar legal entities, (2) Evaluating fees paid to a decision maker or a service\rprovider as a variable interest, (3) The effect of fee arrangements on the primary beneficiary determination, (4) The effect of\rrelated parties on the primary beneficiary determination, and (5) Certain investment funds. The amendments in this Update are effective\rfor public business entities for fiscal years, and for interim periods within those fiscal years, beginning after December 15,\r2015. For all other entities, the amendments in this Update are effective for fiscal years beginning after December 15, 2016, and\rfor interim periods within fiscal years beginning after December 15, 2017. Early adoption is permitted, including adoption in an\rinterim period. If an entity early adopts the amendments in an interim period, any adjustments should be reflected as of the beginning\rof the fiscal year that includes that interim period. A reporting entity may apply the amendments in this Update using a modified\rretrospective approach by recording a cumulative-effect adjustment to equity as of the beginning of the fiscal year of adoption.\rA reporting entity also may apply the amendments retrospectively. The Company is currently assessing this guidance for future implementation. In December 2014, the FASB issued ASU\r2014-18, Business Combinations (Topic 805): Accounting for Identifiable Intangible Assets in a Business Combination. ASU 2014-18\relects the accounting alternative to recognize or otherwise consider the fair value of intangible assets as a result of any in-scope\rtransactions and states that they should no longer recognized separately from goodwill (1) customer-related intangible assets unless\rthey are capable of being sold or licensed independently from other assets of the business and (2) non-competition agreements.\rThe amendments in ASU 2014-18 will be effective prospectively for annual reporting periods beginning after December 15, 2015 and\rthe effective date of adoption will begin on the timing of that first in-scope transaction. The Company has not adopted ASU 2014-18\rduring the year ended December 31, 2014. In August 2014, the FASB issued ASU\rNo. 2014-15, &#34;Presentation of Financial Statements - Going Concern &#34;. The amendments in this update provide guidance\rin U.S. GAAP about management's responsibilities to evaluate whether there is substantial doubt about an entity's ability to continue\ras a going concern and to provide related footnote disclosures. The main provision of the amendments are for an entity's management,\rin connection with the preparation of financial statements, to evaluate whether there are conditions or events, considered in the\raggregate, that raise substantial doubt about the entity's ability to continue as a going concern within one year after the date\rthat the financial statements are issued. Management's evaluation should be based on relevant conditions and events that are known\ror reasonably knowable at the date the financial statements are issued. When management identifies conditions or events that raise\rsubstantial doubt about an entity's ability to continue as a going concern, the entity should disclose information that enables\rusers of the financial statements to understand all of the following: (1) principal conditions or events that raised substantial\rdoubt about the entity's ability to continue as a going concern (before consideration of management's plans); (2) management's\revaluation of the significance of those conditions or events in relation to the entity's ability to meet its obligations; and (3)\rmanagement's plans that alleviated substantial doubt about the entity's ability to continue as a going concern or management's\rplans that are intended to mitigate the conditions or events that raise substantial doubt about the entity's ability to continue\ras a going concern. The amendments in this update are effective for interim and annual reporting periods after December 15, 2016\rand early application is permitted. The Company is currently assessing this guidance for future implementation.  In June 2014, the FASB issued ASU 2014-10, Development\rStage Entities (Topic 915): Elimination of Certain Financial Reporting Requirements. ASU 2014-10 eliminates the distinction of\ra development stage entity and certain related disclosure requirements, including the elimination of inception-to-date information\ron the statements of operations, cash flows and stockholders' equity. The amendments in ASU 2014-10 will be effective prospectively\rfor annual reporting periods beginning after December 15, 2014, and interim periods within those annual periods, however early\radoption is permitted. The Company adopted ASU 2014-10 during the year ended December 31, 2014, thereby no longer presenting or\rdisclosing any information required by Topic 915. In May 2014, the FASB issued ASU\rNo. 2014-09, &#34;Revenue from Contracts with Customers (Topic 606)&#34; (&#34;ASU 2014-09&#34;). ASU 2014-09 amends the\rguidance for revenue recognition to replace numerous, industry specific requirements and converges areas under this topic\rwith those of the International Financial Reporting Standards. The ASU implements a five-step process for customer contract\rrevenue recognition that focuses on transfer of control, as opposed to transfer of risk and rewards. The amendment also\rrequires enhanced disclosures regarding the nature, amount, timing and uncertainty of revenues and cash flows from contracts\rwith customers. Other major provisions include the capitalization and amortization of certain contract costs, ensuring the\rtime value of money is considered in the transaction price, and allowing estimates of variable consideration to be recognized\rbefore contingencies are resolved in certain circumstances. The amendments in this ASU are effective for reporting periods\rbeginning after December 15, 2016, and early adoption is prohibited. Entities can transition to the standard either\rretrospectively or as a cumulative-effect adjustment as of the date of adoption. We are currently assessing the impact the\radoption of ASU 2014-09 will have on our financial statements and disclosures. EQUITY BASED PAYMENTS TO NON-EMPLOYEES The Company applied the Financial Accounting\rStandards Board&#146;s Accounting Standards Codification Topic 505 related to Equity Based Payments to Non-Employees to account\rfor these options and warrants issued. According to Topic 505, all transactions in which goods or services are the consideration\rreceived for the issuance of equity instruments shall be accounted for based on the fair value of the consideration received or\rthe fair value of the equity instruments issued, whichever is more reliably measurable. The Company believes that fair value of\rthese options and warrants is a more reliable measure of the consideration received for services performed for the Company. We\rdetermined the fair value of these equity instruments using the Black-Scholes option-pricing model. Factors used in the determination\rof the fair value of these equity instruments include, the stock price at the grant date, the exercise price, the expected life\rof the equity instrument, the volatility of the underlying stock, the expected dividends on it, and the risk-free interest rate\rover the expected life of the equity instrument."
