S"NOTE 2 - Summary of Significant Accounting Policies Basis of Consolidation The consolidated financial statements include the accounts\rof BioZone Pharmaceuticals, Inc. and its subsidiaries, all of which are wholly owned, its equity investment in BetaZone Laboratories,\rLLC, and 580 Garcia Ave, LLC, a Variable Interest Entity (&#147;VIE&#148;). The Company considered the terms of its interest in 580 Garcia\rand determined that it was a variable interest entity (VIE) in accordance with ACS 810-10-55, and that it should be consolidated\rwith the Company.  As of December 31, 2011, amounts relating to 580 Garcia included in the consolidated assets, which\rare shown in Property and Equipment, and consolidated liabilities, which are reported in long-term debt, total $758,894 and $2,582,818,\rrespectively. The Company rents the manufacturing facility located at 580 Garcia Avenue, Pittsburg CA from 580 Garcia, is the sole\rtenant and is a guarantor of the mortgage note issued by 580 Garcia to GECC, the lien holder on the property. The Company&#146;s\rmaximum exposure to loss, which is based on the Company&#146;s guarantee of the mortgage note of 580 Garcia owed to GECC,\ris $2,582,818, which equals the carrying amount of the liability as of December 31, 2012. Our significant unconsolidated subsidiary that is accounted\rfor using the equity method of accounting is our investment in Betazone Laboratories LLC. Use of Estimates The preparation of the financial statements in conformity\rwith Generally Accepted Accounting Principles (&#147;GAAP&#148;) requires management to make estimates and assumptions that affect\rthe reported amounts of assets and liabilities and disclosure of contingent assets and liabilities at the dates of the financial\rstatements and the reported amounts of revenue and expenses during the reporting periods. Actual results could differ from those\restimates. These estimates and assumptions include the collectability of accounts receivable and deferred taxes and related valuation\rallowances. Certain of our estimates, including evaluating the collectability of accounts receivable, could be affected by external\rconditions, including those unique to our industry, and general economic conditions. It is possible that these external factors\rcould have an effect on our estimates that could cause actual results to differ from our estimates. We re-evaluate all of our accounting\restimates at least quarterly based on these conditions and record adjustments when necessary. Cash and Cash Equivalents We consider all short-term highly liquid investments with\ran original maturity at the date of purchase of three months or less to be cash equivalents. Revenue Recognition We follow the guidance of the Securities and Exchange Commission&#146;s\rStaff Accounting Bulletin (&#147;SAB&#148;) 104 for revenue recognition and Accounting Standards Codification (&#147;ASC&#148;)\rTopic 605, &#147;Revenue Recognition&#148;. The Company operates as a contract manufacturer and produces finished goods according\rto customer specifications. The agreements with customers do not contain any rights of return other than for goods that fail to\rmeet the specifications provided by the customer. The Company has not experienced any significant returns from customers and accordingly,\rin management&#146;s opinion, no reserve for returns is provided. We record revenue when persuasive evidence of an arrangement\rexists, services have been rendered or product delivery has occurred, the selling price to the customer is fixed or determinable\rand collectability of the revenue is reasonably assured. Accounts Receivable and Allowance\rfor Doubtful Accounts Receivable We have a policy of reserving for uncollectible accounts\rbased on our best estimate of the amount of probable credit losses in our existing accounts receivable. We extend credit to our\rcustomers based on an evaluation of their financial condition and other factors. We generally do not require collateral or other\rsecurity to support accounts receivable. We perform ongoing credit evaluations of our customers and maintain an allowance for potential\rbad debts if required.  We determine whether an allowance for doubtful accounts is required by evaluating specific accounts\rwhere information indicates the customers may have an inability to meet financial obligations. In these cases, we use assumptions\rand judgment, based on the best available facts and circumstances, to record a specific allowance for those customers against amounts\rdue to reduce the receivable to the amount expected to be collected. These specific allowances are re-evaluated and adjusted as\radditional information is received. The amounts calculated are analyzed to determine the total amount of the allowance. We may\ralso record a general allowance as necessary.  Direct write-offs are taken in the period when we have exhausted our efforts\rto collect overdue and unpaid receivables or otherwise evaluate other circumstances that indicate that we should abandon such efforts. Inventories Inventories are stated at the lower of cost, determined using\rthe weighted average cost method, and net realizable value. Net realizable value is the estimated selling price, in the ordinary\rcourse of business, less estimated costs to complete and dispose of the product. If the Company identifies excess, obsolete or unsalable items,\rits inventories are written down to their realizable value in the period in which the impairment is first identified. During the\ryear ended December 31, 2012 we recorded a charge to cost of sales of $405,918 while in the prior year period we charged $1,439,616\rrelating to the write-down of inventory due to obsolescence.  Shipping and handling costs incurred for inventory purchases\rand product shipments are recorded in cost of sales in the Company's consolidated statements of operations. Fair Value Measurements We adopted the provisions of ASC Topic 820, &#147;Fair Value\rMeasurements and Disclosures&#148;, which defines fair value as used in numerous accounting pronouncements, establishes a framework\rfor measuring fair value and expands disclosure of fair value measurements. The estimated fair value of certain financial instruments,\rincluding cash and cash equivalents, accounts receivable, accounts payable and accrued expenses are carried at historical cost\rbasis, which approximates their fair values because of the short-term nature of these instruments. The carrying amounts of our\rshort and long term credit obligations approximate fair value because the effective yields on these obligations, which include\rcontractual interest rates taken together with other features such as concurrent issuances of warrants and/or embedded conversion\roptions, are comparable to rates of returns for instruments of similar credit risk. ASC 820 defines fair value as the exchange price that would\rbe received for an asset or paid to transfer a liability (an exit price) in the principal or most advantageous market for the asset\ror liability in an orderly transaction between market participants on the measurement date. ASC 820 also establishes a fair value\rhierarchy, which requires an entity to maximize the use of observable inputs and minimize the use of unobservable inputs when measuring\rfair value. ASC 820 describes three levels of inputs that may be used to measure fair value: Level 1 &#151; quoted prices in active\rmarkets for identical assets or liabilitiesLevel 2 &#151; quoted prices for similar\rassets and liabilities in active markets or inputs that are observableLevel 3 &#151; inputs that are unobservable\r(for example cash flow modeling inputs based on assumptions) The warrant liabilities issued in connection with our convertible\rdebt, classified as a level 3 liability, are the only financial liability measured at fair value on a recurring basis We measure derivative liabilities at fair value using the\rBlack-Scholes option pricing model with assumptions that include the fair value of the stock underlying the derivative instrument,\rthe exercise or conversion price of the derivative instrument, the risk free interest rate for a term comparable to the term of\rthe derivative instrument and the volatility rate and dividend yield for our common stock. For derivative instruments convertible\rinto or exercisable for shares of our preferred stock, we considered the price per share of $.50 paid by unrelated parties as the\rfair value of our common stock. For derivative instruments convertible into or exercisable for shares of our common stock, we considered\rthe results of a valuation performed by a third party specialist and other internal analyses performed by management to determine\rthe value of our stock at the commitment dates of applicable transactions. The risk-free rate is based on the U.S. Treasury yield\rcurve in effect at the time of grant. The Company has not paid dividends to date and does not expect to pay dividends in the foreseeable\rfuture due to its substantial accumulated deficit. Accordingly, expected dividends yields are currently zero. Expected volatility\ris based principally on an analysis of historical volatilities of similarly situated companies in the marketplace for a number\rof periods that is at least equal to the contractual term or estimated life of the applicable financial instrument. We also considered the use of the lattice or binomial models\rwith respect to valuing derivative financial instruments that feature anti-dilution price protection; however, the differences\rin the results are insignificant due to the low probability of triggering price adjustments in such financial instruments Stock-based compensation We recognize compensation expense for stock-based compensation\rin accordance with ASC Topic 718. For employee stock-based awards, we calculate the fair value of the award on the date of grant\rusing the Black-Scholes method for stock options and the quoted price of our common stock for unrestricted shares; the expense\ris recognized over the service period for awards expected to vest. For non-employee stock-based awards, we calculate the fair value\rof the award on the date of grant in the same manner as employee awards. However, the awards are revalued at the end of each reporting\rperiod and the pro rata compensation expense is adjusted accordingly until such time the nonemployee award is fully vested, at\rwhich time the total compensation recognized to date equals the fair value of the stock-based award as calculated on the measurement\rdate, which is the date at which the award recipient&#146;s performance is complete. The estimation of stock-based awards that\rwill ultimately vest requires judgment, and to the extent actual results or updated estimates differ from original estimates, such\ramounts are recorded as a cumulative adjustment in the period estimates are revised. We consider many factors when estimating expected\rforfeitures, including types of awards, employee class, and historical experience. Property and equipment Property and equipment are stated at cost less accumulated\rdepreciation. Depreciation is provided for on a straight-line basis over the useful lives of the assets. Expenditures for additions\rand improvements are capitalized; repairs and maintenance are expensed as incurred. Goodwill Goodwill represents the excess of the consideration transferred\rover the fair value of net assets of business purchased. Goodwill is not being amortized but is evaluated for impairment on at\rleast an annual basis. Impairment of long lived assets Long-lived assets are reviewed for impairment when circumstances\rindicate the carrying value of an asset may not be recoverable. For assets that are to be held and used, impairment is recognized\rwhen the estimated undiscounted cash flows associated with the asset or group of assets is less than their carrying value. If impairment\rexists, an adjustment is made to write the asset down to its fair value, and a loss is recorded as the difference between the carrying\rvalue and fair value. Fair values are determined based on quoted market values, discounted cash flows or internal and external\rappraisals, as applicable. Assets to be disposed of are carried at the lower of carrying value or estimated net realizable value. Income taxes We use the asset and liability method of accounting for income\rtaxes in accordance with ASC Topic 740, &#147;Income Taxes.&#148; Under this method, income tax expense is recognized for the\ramount of: (i) taxes payable or refundable for the current year and (ii) deferred tax consequences of temporary differences resulting\rfrom matters that have been recognized in an entity&#146;s financial statements or tax returns. Deferred tax assets and liabilities\rare measured using enacted tax rates expected to apply to taxable income in the years in which those temporary differences are\rexpected to be recovered or settled. The effect on deferred tax assets and liabilities of a change in tax rates is recognized in\rthe results of operations in the period that includes the enactment date. A valuation allowance is provided to reduce the deferred\rtax assets reported if based on the weight of the available positive and negative evidence, it is more likely than not some portion\ror all of the deferred tax assets will not be realized. ASC Topic 740.10.30 clarifies the accounting for uncertainty\rin income taxes recognized in an enterprise&#146;s financial statements and prescribes a recognition threshold and measurement\rattribute for the financial statement recognition and measurement of a tax position taken or expected to be taken in a tax return.\rASC Topic 740.10.40 provides guidance on de-recognition, classification, interest and penalties, accounting in interim periods,\rdisclosure, and transition. We have no material uncertain tax positions for any of the reporting periods presented. Convertible Instruments We evaluate and account for conversion options embedded in\rconvertible instruments in accordance with ASC 815 &#147;Derivatives and Hedging Activities&#148;. Applicable GAAP requires companies to bifurcate conversion\roptions from their host instruments and account for them as free standing derivative financial instruments according to certain\rcriteria. The criteria include circumstances in which (a) the economic characteristics and risks of the embedded derivative instrument\rare not clearly and closely related to the economic characteristics and risks of the host contract, (b) the hybrid instrument that\rembodies both the embedded derivative instrument and the host contract is not re-measured at fair value under other GAAP with changes\rin fair value reported in earnings as they occur and (c) a separate instrument with the same terms as the embedded derivative instrument\rwould be considered a derivative instrument. We account for convertible instruments (when we have determined\rthat the embedded conversion options should not be bifurcated from their host instruments) as follows: We record when necessary,\rdiscounts to convertible notes for the intrinsic value of conversion options embedded in debt instruments based upon the differences\rbetween the fair value of the underlying common stock at the commitment date of the note transaction and the effective conversion\rprice embedded in the note. Debt discounts under these arrangements are amortized over the term of the related debt to their stated\rdate of redemption. The embedded conversion option in connection with our convertible debt could not be exercised unless and until\rwe completed a Qualifying Financing transaction. Accordingly, we determined based on authoritative guidance that the embedded conversion\roption is deemed to be a contingent conversion rather than active conversion option that did not require accounting recognition\rat the commitment dates of the issuances of the Notes. Common Stock Purchase Warrants and\rOther Derivative Financial Instruments We classify as equity any contracts that require physical\rsettlement or net-share settlement or provide us a choice of net-cash settlement or settlement in our own shares (physical settlement\ror net-share settlement) provided that such contracts are indexed to our own stock as defined in ASC 815-40 (&#34;Contracts in\rEntity's Own Equity&#34;). We classify as assets or liabilities any contracts that require net-cash settlement (including a requirement\rto net cash settle the contract if an event occurs and if that event is outside our control) or give the counterparty a choice\rof net-cash settlement or settlement in shares (physical settlement or net-share settlement). We assess classification of our common\rstock purchase warrants and other free standing derivatives at each reporting date to determine whether a change in classification\rbetween assets and liabilities is required. Our derivative instruments consisting of warrants to purchase\rour common stock were valued using the Black-Scholes option pricing model, using the following assumptions at December 31, 2012:  Concentration of Credit Risk Financial instruments that potentially expose us to concentrations\rof credit risk consist principally of cash and cash equivalents. We maintain our cash accounts at high quality financial institutions\rwith balances, at times, in excess of Federally insured limits. Management believes that the financial institutions that hold our\rdeposits are financially sound and therefore pose minimal credit risk Research and development Research and development expenditures are charged to operations\ras incurred Going concern The continuation of the Company as a going concern is dependent\rupon, among other things, the attainment of profitable operations and the ability of the Company to obtain necessary equity or\rdebt financing.  These factors, among others, raise substantial doubt regarding the Company&#146;s ability to continue\ras a going concern. Accordingly, the audit report prepared by our independent registered public accounting firm relating to the\rconsolidated financial statements for the year ended December 31, 2012 and December 31, 2011 includes an explanatory paragraph\rexpressing substantial doubt about its ability to continue as a going concern.  Our auditor&#146;s going concern opinion\rmay have a detrimental effect on our ability to obtain additional funding."
