S"Basis of Presentation This summary of significant\raccounting policies of the Company is presented to assist in understanding the Company&#146;s financial statements.  The\rfinancial statements and notes are representations of the Company&#146;s management, which is responsible for their integrity\rand objectivity.  These accounting policies conform to accounting principles generally accepted in the United States\rof America (&#147;GAAP&#148;) and have been consistently applied in the preparation of the financial statements.  Principles of Consolidation The consolidated\rfinancial statements include the financial statements of the Company and its subsidiaries, Massive Media Pty Ltd., Massive Interactive\rMedia Ltd., and Wunderkind Group Pty Ltd.  As part of the acquisition of Massive Media Pty Ltd and its controlled entities\rby the Company, it discontinued all oil and gas operations related to properties owned in Texas and Oklahoma.  Financial\rresults related to the oil and gas operations are reported as discontinued operations beginning with the financial results as of\rDecember 31, 2013 (See Note 5Discontinued Operations and Assets Held for Sale). Use of Estimates The preparation of\rconsolidated financial statements in conformity with accounting principles generally accepted in the United States requires management\rto make estimates and assumptions that affect the reported amounts of assets and liabilities and disclosures of contingent assets\rand liabilities at the date of the financial statements and the reported amounts of revenue and expenses during the reporting period.  Actual\rresults could differ from those estimates. On an ongoing basis,\rthe Company evaluates its estimates, including those related to the accounts receivable allowance, the useful lives of long-lived\rassets and other intangible assets, and income taxes, among others.  The Company bases its estimates on historical experience\rand on various other assumptions that are believed to be reasonable, the results of which form the basis for making judgments about\rthe carrying value of assets and liabilities as well as reported revenue and expenses during the periods presented. Cash and Cash Equivalents Cash and cash equivalents\rrepresent cash on hand and deposits held at call with banks.  The Company considers all highly liquid investments with\roriginal maturities of three months or less at the time of purchase to be cash equivalents. Fair Value of Financial Instruments Pursuant to the Accounting\rStandards Codification (&#147;ASC&#148;) No. 820, &#147;Disclosures About Fair Value of Financial Instruments&#148;,\rthe Company records its financial assets and liabilities at fair value.  ASC No. 820 provides a framework for measuring\rfair value, clarifies the definition of fair value and expands disclosures regarding fair value measurements. Fair\rvalue is defined as the price that would be received to sell an asset or paid to transfer a liability (an exit price) in an orderly\rtransaction between market participants at the reporting date.  ASC No. 820 establishes a three-tier hierarchy, which\rprioritizes the inputs used in the valuation methodologies in measuring fair value: Level 1&#151;Inputs are unadjusted,\rquoted prices in active markets for identical assets or liabilities at the measurement date. Level 2&#151;Inputs (other than quoted\rprices included in Level 1) are either directly or indirectly observable for the asset or liability through correlation with market\rdata at the measurement date and for the duration of the asset/liability&#146;s anticipated life. Level 3&#151;Inputs reflect management&#146;s\rbest estimate of what market participants would use in pricing the asset or liability at the measurement date. Consideration is\rgiven to the risk inherent in the valuation technique and the risk inherent in the inputs to the model. The carrying values\rfor cash and cash equivalents, accounts receivable, other current assets, accounts payable and accrued liabilities approximate\rtheir fair value due to their short maturities.  Accounts Receivable Receivables from\rservices are recognized and carried at the original invoice amount less allowance for any uncollectible amounts. Management periodically\rreviews receivables for collectability.  An estimate for doubtful accounts is made when collection of the full amount\ris no longer probable.  Uncollectible receivables are charged off against the allowance account.   An allowance\rfor doubtful accounts of $207,506 and $0 was recorded as of December 31, 2014 and 2013, respectively. The Company did not\rhave any off balance-sheet credit exposure relating to its customers, suppliers or others. Concentration of Credit Risk Financial instruments\rthat potentially expose the Company to concentrations of credit risk consist primarily of cash and cash equivalents and accounts\rreceivable for which the carrying amounts approximate fair value.  The Company places their cash and cash equivalents\rwith financial institutions with high-credit ratings and quality. The Company conducts\rcredit evaluations of customers and generally does not require collateral or other security from customers.  The Company\restablishes an allowance for doubtful accounts primarily based upon the age of the receivables and factors relevant to determining\rthe credit risk of specific customers.  The amount of receivables ultimately not collected by the Company has generally\rbeen consistent with management&#146;s expectations and the allowance established for doubtful accounts. Major customers The Company has 2\rsignificant customers, which accounted for 15% and 27% of the revenues for the year ended December 31, 2014.  The Company&#146;s\rsales to its top five customers accounted for approximately 66% and 27% of revenues during the year ended December 31, 2014 and\r2013, respectively.  These customers accounted for approximately 84% and 34% of accounts receivable balance as of December\r31, 2014 and 2013, respectively. Major suppliers The Company had purchases\rfrom five vendors that accounted for approximately 25% and 51% of purchases during the year ended December 31, 2014 and December\r31, 2013, respectively.  These vendors accounted for approximately 22% and 11% of accounts payable balance as of period\rended December 31, 2014 and December 31, 2013, respectively. Segment Reporting ASC 280,Segment\rReporting, establishes standards for reporting information about operating segments.  Operating segments are defined\ras components of an enterprise about which separate financial information is available that is evaluated regularly by the chief\roperating decision maker, or decision making group, in deciding how to allocate resources and in assessing performance.  The\rGroup&#146;s chief operating decision maker is the Chief Executive Officer, who reviews consolidated results of operations prepared\rin accordance with US GAAP when making decisions about allocating resources and assessing performance of the Group; hence, the\rGroup has only one operating segment, namely the software development services. Income Taxes The Company recognizes\rdeferred income tax liabilities and assets for the expected future income tax consequences of temporary differences between financial\raccounting bases and income tax bases of assets and liabilities.  Deferred income taxes are measured by applying currently\renacted income tax rates.  The Company accounts for uncertainty in income taxes for income tax positions taken or expected\rto be taken in an income tax return.  Only income tax positions that meet the more-likely-than-not recognition threshold\rwill be recognized. This process includes\ran analysis of whether tax positions the Company takes with regard to a particular item of income or deduction would meet the definition\rof an uncertain tax position under the standards.  Management believes that tax positions taken by the Company with regard\rto income and deduction do not constitute any uncertain tax positions under the standards. Goods and Services Tax/Value Added\rTax The Company's Australian\roperations are subject to the Goods and Services Tax on revenue sales of 10%. The Company's English operations are subject to the\rValue Added Tax on revenue sales of 20%. Revenue Recognition The Company recognizes\rrevenue when it is realized and earned. Specifically, the Company recognizes revenue when services are performed and projects are\rcompleted and accepted by the customer. The Company recognizes\rrevenue in accordance with the Financial Accounting Standards Board&#146;s (FASB) Accounting Standards Codification (&#147;ASC&#148;)\r985-605 &#147;Software - Revenue Recognition&#148;. Project Services Revenue Revenue derived from\rservices primarily includes consulting, implementation, and training.  Fees are primarily billed under time and materials\rarrangements and are recognized as services are performed. License Fees Revenue License revenue in\rconnection with license agreements for standard proprietary software is recognized upon delivery of the software, provided collection\ris considered probable and the fee is fixed or determinable. Support Revenue Revenue derived from\rtechnical support contracts primarily includes telephone consulting and on-site support as well as error reporting and correction\rservices.  Maintenance contracts are typically sold for a separate fee with initial contractual period of one year with\rrenewal for additional periods thereafter.  Technical support service revenue is recognized ratably over the term of\rthe service agreement. Deferred Revenue Deferred revenue\rrepresents advance payments or billings for software licenses, services, and maintenance.  Cost\rof Revenues Cost of revenues\rfor licenses includes amortization of capitalized computer software development costs.  Costs for maintenance and services\rrevenues include the cost of personnel to conduct implementations, customer support and consulting, and other personnel-related\rexpenses. Foreign Currency Translation The functional currency\rof the Massive Media Pty Ltd. and Wunderkind Group Pty Ltd. is Australian Dollars (&#147;AUD&#148;). The functional currency\rof Massive Interactive Media Ltd is Great British Pounds (&#34;GBP&#34;). For financial reporting\rpurposes, the financial statements of the Company and its subsidiaries, which are prepared using each entity's functional currency,\rare translated into the Company&#146;s reporting currency, the United States Dollar (&#147;USD&#148;).  Assets and\rliabilities are translated using the exchange rate at each balance sheet date.  Revenue and expenses are translated using\raverage rates prevailing during each reporting period, and shareholders&#146; equity is translated at historical exchange rates.  Adjustments\rresulting from the translation are recorded as a separate component of accumulated other comprehensive income in shareholders&#146;\requity. The exchange rates\rapplied are as follows:  Property and Equipment Furniture and office\requipment, electronic equipment and motor vehicles are recorded at cost less accumulated depreciation.  Depreciation\ris calculated based on estimated useful life of the assets.  When furniture and\roffice equipment, electronic equipment and motor vehicles are retired or otherwise disposed of, resulting gain or loss is included\rin net income or loss in the year of disposition for the difference between the net book value and proceeds received thereon. Maintenance\rand repairs which do not improve or extend the expected useful lives of the assets are charged to expenses as incurred.  Impairment of Long-Lived Assets In accordance with\rImpairment or Disposal of Long-Lived Assets Subsections of FASB ASC Subtopic 360-10,Property, Plant, and Equipment - Overall,\rlong-lived assets, such as property, plant and equipment, and purchased intangible assets subject to amortization, are reviewed\rfor impairment whenever events or changes in circumstances indicate that the carrying amount of an asset may not be recoverable.  If\rcircumstances require a long-lived asset or asset group be tested for possible impairment, the Company first compares undiscounted\rcash flows expected to be generated by that asset or asset group to its carrying value.  If the carrying value of the\rlong-lived asset or asset group is not recoverable on an undiscounted cash flow basis, an impairment is recognized to the extent\rthat the carrying value exceeds its fair value.  Fair value is determined through various valuation techniques including\rdiscounted cash flow models, quoted market values and third-party independent appraisals, as considered necessary.  No\rimpairment of long-lived assets was recognized for the period ended December 31, 2014 and year ended December 31, 2013 respectively.   Capitalized\rComputer Software Development Costs The Company capitalizes\rsoftware development costs in accordance with the FASB ASC Topic 985-20Costs of Software to be Sold, Leased or Marketed.  All\rsoftware development costs are capitalized and reported at the lower of unamortized cost or net realizable value. Capitalization\rceases when the product or enhancement is available for general release to customers. The Company makes\rongoing evaluations of the recoverability of its capitalized software projects by comparing the net amount capitalized for each\rproduct to the estimated net realizable value of the product.  If such evaluations indicate that the unamortized software\rdevelopment costs exceed the net realizable value, the Company writes off the amount by which the unamortized software development\rcosts exceed net realizable value.  The Company's capitalized computer software development costs are being amortized\rratably based on the projected revenues associated with the related software or on a straight-line basis over five years, whichever\rmethod results in a higher level of amortization. Intangible Assets The Company amortizes\rintangible assets on a straight line basis over their estimated useful lives, generally as follows: four to nine years for software,\rten to twenty years for customer relationships and trade names, and one to five years for other intangible assets, except goodwill.\rGoodwill is not amortized, but subject to impairment testing.  Operating Leases Leases where substantially\rall the rewards and risks of ownership of assets remain with the lesser are accounted for as operating leases. Payments made under\roperating leases are charged to the consolidated statements of operations on a straight-line basis over the lease periods. The Company leases\roffice rental spaces in Sydney, Australia and London, England. Derivative Instruments The Company&#146;s\rdebt or equity instruments may contain embedded derivative instruments, such as conversion options, which in certain circumstances\rmay be required to be bifurcated from the associated host instrument and accounted for separately as a derivative instrument liability. The identification\rof, and accounting for, derivative instruments is complex.  The Company&#146;s derivative instrument liabilities are\rre-valued at the end of each reporting period, with changes in the fair value of the derivative liability recorded as charges or\rcredits to income, in the period in which the changes occur.  For bifurcated conversion options related to the notes\rissued in 2011 (see Note 15Borrowings)that are accounted for as derivative instrument liabilities, the Company determines\rthe fair value of these instruments using binomial option pricing model.  That model requires assumptions related to\rthe remaining term of the instrument and risk-free rates of return, the Company&#146;s current Common Stock price and expected\rdividend yield, and the expected volatility of the Company&#146;s Common Stock price over the life of the option. For the bifurcated\rconversion option related to the convertible note issued in 2014 (see Note 15Borrowings) in connection with the Wunderkind\rAcquisition, the Company determined the fair value of the instruments using the Monte Carlo Valuation Model, due to the multitude\rof possible outcomes for the instrument.  This model requires assumptions related to the remaining term of the instrument\rand risk-free rates of return, the Company's current Common Stock price and expected dividend yield, and the expected volatility\rof the Company's Common Stock price over the life of the option. Deemed dividend We incur a deemed\rdividend on Series B Preferred Redeemable Stock. As the conversion rate was less than the deemed fair value of the Common Stock\rof $0.20, the Series B Preferred Redeemable Stock contains a beneficial conversion feature as described in ASC 470.  The\rdifference in the stated conversion price and estimated fair value of the Common Stock is accounted for as a beneficial conversion\rfeature and affects income or loss available to common stockholders for purposes of EPS.   Earnings per Share The Company adopted\rASC 260, &#34;Earnings Per Share&#34; (&#34;EPS&#34;), which requires presentation of basic and diluted EPS on the face of\rthe income statement for all entities with complex capital structures, and requires a reconciliation of the numerator and denominator\rof the basic EPS computation to the numerator and denominator of the diluted EPS computation.  In the accompanying financial\rstatements, basic earnings (loss) per share is computed by dividing net income (loss) applicable to common stockholders by the\rweighted average number of shares of Common Stock outstanding during the period.  Diluted net income per common share\ris computed by dividing the net income applicable to common stockholders, adjusted on an &#34;as if converted&#34; basis, by\rthe weighted average number of common shares outstanding plus potential dilutive securities.  Diluted EPS excluded all\rdilutive potential shares if their effect is anti-dilutive.   The following sets\rforth the computation of diluted EPS for the year ended December 31, 2014:   Basic net income\rper share is based on the weighted average number of common and common equivalent shares outstanding.  Potential common\rshares includable in the computation of fully diluted per share results are not presented for the year ended December 31, 2013\rin the consolidated financial statements as their effect would be anti-dilutive.  The total number of shares issuable upon\rconversion of preferred shares that were not included in dilutive earnings per share for the year ended December 31, 2014 was 15,544,523. Net Income (Loss) Attributable to Common Shares The Company is required\rto provide basic and dilutive earnings per common share information.  The basic net loss per common share is computed\rby dividing the net loss applicable to common stockholders by the weighted average number of common shares outstanding.  Diluted\rnet loss per common share is computed by dividing the net loss applicable to common stockholders, adjusted on an &#34;as if converted&#34;\rbasis, by the weighted average number of common shares outstanding plus potential dilutive securities.  For the years\rended December 31, 2014 and 2013, there were 52,404,633 and 0 shares, respectively. Commitments and Contingencies In the normal course\rof business, the Company is subject to loss contingencies, such as legal proceedings and claims arising out of its business, that\rcover a wide range of matters, including, among others, government investigations, product and environmental liability, and tax\rmatters.  In accordance with ASC 450-20,Accounting for Contingencies, the Company records accruals for such loss\rcontingencies when it is probable that a liability has been incurred and the amount of loss can be reasonably estimated.  Historically,\rthe Company has not experienced any material service liability claims. Recent Accounting Pronouncements We have adopted recently\rissued accounting pronouncements and have determined that they have no material effect on our financial position, results of operations,\ror cash flow.  We do not expect any recently issued but not yet adopted accounting pronouncements to have a material\reffect on our financial position, results of operations or cash flow. In July 2012, the\rFASB issued ASU No. 2012-02, Intangibles-Goodwill and Other (Topic 350): Testing Indefinite-Lived Intangible Assets for Impairment\r(&#147;ASU 2012-02&#148;), allowing entities the option to first assess qualitative factors to determine whether it is necessary\rto perform the quantitative impairment test.  If the qualitative assessment indicates it is more-likely-than-not that\rthe fair value of an indefinite-lived intangible asset is less than its carrying amount, the quantitative impairment test is required.  Otherwise,\rno testing is required. ASU 2012-02 is effective for reporting periods beginning January 1, 2013.  The adoption of this\rupdate did not have a material impact on the consolidated financial statements but may have an impact in future periods. In February 2013,\rthe FASB issued ASU 2013-02, Comprehensive Income (Topic 220): Reporting of Amounts Reclassified Out of Accumulated Other Comprehensive\rIncome (&#147;ASU 2013-02&#148;).  ASU 2013-02 is intended to improve the reporting of reclassifications out of accumulated\rother comprehensive income.  Accordingly, an entity is required to report the effect of significant reclassifications\rout of accumulated other comprehensive income on the respective line items in net income if the amount being reclassified is required\runder GAAP to be reclassified in its entirety to net income.  For other amounts that are not required under GAAP to be\rreclassified in their entirety to net income in the same reporting period, an entity is required to cross-reference other disclosures\rrequired under GAAP that provide additional detail about those amounts.  ASU 2013-02 is effective for reporting periods\rbeginning after December 15, 2012.  The Company adopted ASU 2013-02 effective January 1, 2013 and the adoption did not\rhave a material impact on the Company&#146;s consolidated financial statements. In March 2013 the\rFASB issued ASU 2013-05,Parent&#146;s Accounting for the Cumulative Translation Adjustment upon Derecognition of Certain Subsidiaries\ror Groups of Assets within a Foreign Entity or of an Investment in a Foreign Entity.  This standard is an update\rto clarify existing guidance for the release of cumulative translation adjustments into net income when a parent sells all or a\rpart of its investment in a foreign entity or achieves a business combination of a foreign entity in stages.  The amendments\rin this Update are effective prospectively for fiscal years (and interim reporting periods within those years) beginning after\rDecember 15, 2013.  The adoption of this guidance did not have a material impact on the Company's results of operations,\rcash flows or financial position. In July 2013 the\rFASB issued ASU 2013-11,Presentation of an Unrecognized Tax Benefit When a Net Operating Loss Carryforward, a Similar Tax Loss,\ror a Tax Credit Carryforward Exists.  This guidance to require standard presentation of an unrecognized tax benefit\rwhen a carryforward related to net operating losses or tax credits exists.  The amendments in this Update are effective\rfor fiscal years, and interim periods within those years, beginning after December 15, 2013.  The adoption of this guidance\rdid not have a material impact on the Company's results of operations, cash flows or financial position. In May 2014 the FASB\rissued ASU 2014-09,Revenue from Contracts with Customers, as a new Topic, Accounting Standards Codification (ASC) Topic\r606.  The new revenue recognition standard provides a five-step analysis of transactions to determine when and how revenue\ris recognized.  The core principle is that a company should recognize revenue to depict the transfer of promised goods or\rservices to customers in an amount that reflects the consideration to which the entity expects to be entitled in exchange for those\rgoods or services.  This ASU is effective for public companies for annual periods beginning after December 15, 2016 (fiscal\r2018) and shall be applied retrospectively to each period presented or as a cumulative-effect adjustment as of the date of adoption. \rThe Company is evaluating the effect of adopting this new accounting guidance. In August 2014, the\rFASB issued ASU 2014-15,Presentation of Financial Statements-Going Concern-Disclosures of Uncertainties about an entity's\rAbility to Continue as a Going Concern (&#34;ASU 2014-15&#34;). ASU 2014-15 provides new guidance related to management's responsibility\rto evaluate whether there is substantial doubt about an entity's ability to continue as a going concern by incorporating and expanding\rupon certain principles that are currently in U.S. auditing standards and to provide related footnote disclosures. This new guidance\ris effective for the annual period ending after December 15, 2016, and for annual periods and interim periods thereafter. The Company\ris currently assessing the impact on the Company's disclosures and financial statements."
