S"Basis of Presentation The accompanying consolidated financial statements\rinclude the accounts of the Company and its wholly owned subsidiaries and have been prepared in accordance with accounting principles\rgenerally accepted in the United States of America.    Reclassifications Certain prior year amounts in the accompanying\rconsolidated financial statements have been reclassified to conform to the current year&#146;s presentation. These reclassifications\rhad no effect on the consolidated results of operations or financial position for any years presented. Principles of Consolidation The accompanying consolidated financial statements\rinclude the accounts of the Company and its wholly-owned subsidiaries. All significant intercompany accounts and transactions have\rbeen eliminated in consolidation. Use of Estimates The preparation of financial statements in\rconformity with GAAP requires management to make estimates and assumptions that affect the amounts reported in the financial statements\rand accompanying notes. These estimates are based on knowledge of current events and anticipated future events and accordingly,\ractual results may differ from those estimates. Risks related to cash The Company maintains cash in bank and deposit\raccounts, which at times may exceed federally insured limits. The Company has not experienced any losses in such accounts. The\rCompany believes it is not exposed to any significant credit risk on cash and cash equivalents. Cash and Cash equivalents The Company considers only highly liquid investments\rsuch as money market funds and commercial paper with maturities of 90 days or less at the date of their acquisition as cash and\rcash equivalents. Fair Value of Financial Instruments The accounting standards regarding disclosures\rabout fair value of financial instruments defines financial instruments and required fair value disclosure of those instruments.\rThis accounting standard defines fair value, establishes a three-level valuation hierarchy for disclosures of fair value measurement\rand enhances disclosure requirements for fair value measures. Receivables, investments, payables, short and long term debt and\rwarrant liabilities qualified as financial instruments. Management believes the carrying amounts of receivables, payables and debt\rare a reasonable estimate of fair value because of the short period of time between the origination of such instruments, their\rexpected realization, and if applicable, their stated interest rate is equivalent to interest rates currently available. The three\rlevels are defined as follows:    The Company analyzes all financial instruments with features of\rboth liabilities and equity under the accounting standards regarding accounting for certain financial instruments with characteristics\rof both liabilities and equity, accounting for derivative instruments and hedging activities, accounting for derivative financial\rinstruments indexed to, and potentially settled in, a company&#146;s own stock, and the accounting standard regarding determining\rwhether an instrument (or embedded feature) is indexed to an entity&#146;s own stock. The accounting standard specifies that a\rcontract that would otherwise meet the definition of a derivative but is both (a) indexed to the Company&#146;s own stock and\r(b) classified in stockholders&#146; equity in the statement of financial position would not be considered a derivative financial\rinstrument. This standard provides a two-step model to be applied in determining whether a financial instrument or an embedded\rfeature is indexed to an issuer&#146;s own stock and thus able to qualify for this accounting standard scope exception. All warrants\rissued by the Company are denominated in U.S. dollars. Accounts Receivable Accounts receivable are recorded at the invoice amount and do not\rbear interest. Advertising Cost The Company expenses advertising costs when incurred. Advertising\rexpense for the years ended December 31, 2012 and 2011 was $298,000 and $714,000, respectively. Allowance for Doubtful Accounts Allowance for doubtful accounts is defined as a company's estimate\rof the amount of probable credit losses in the company's existing accounts receivable. The Company does not maintain an allowance\rfor doubtful account based upon management&#146;s review of the Company&#146;s revenue structure whereby substantially all receivables\rare confirmed before they are booked as revenue. The Company reviews its allowance for doubtful accounts policy periodically. The\rCompany does not have any off-balance-sheet exposure related to its customers. Inventory The Inventory balance at December 31, 2011 consisted of credit card\rterminals which were stated at the lower of cost (average) or market. We previously supplied dispensaries with credit card processing\rservices. On October 31, 2011, General Merchant Solutions, our wholly owned subsidiary, discontinued all retail credit card processing\roperations. At December 31, 2012, we did not have any inventory. Property and Equipment Property and equipment are recorded at cost and depreciated using the straight-line method over the useful lives of the assets,\rgenerally from three to seven years. Including accumulated depreciation related to the assets sold with WeedMaps, property\rand equipment at December 31, 2012 and 2011 are presented net of accumulated depreciation of $121,000 and $71,000, respectively. Goodwill In accordance withGoodwill and Other Intangible Assets,\rgoodwill is defined as the excess of the purchase price over the fair value assigned to individual assets acquired and liabilities\rassumed and is tested for impairment at the reporting unit level (operating segment or one level below an operating segment) on\ran annual basis in the Company's fourth fiscal quarter or more frequently if indicators of impairment exist. The performance of\rthe test involves a two-step process. The first step of the impairment test involves comparing the fair value of the Company's\rreporting units with each respective reporting unit's carrying amount, including goodwill. The fair value of reporting units is\rgenerally determined using the income approach. If the carrying amount of a reporting unit exceeds the reporting unit's fair value,\rthe second step of the goodwill impairment test is performed to determine the amount of any impairment loss. The second step of\rthe goodwill impairment test involves comparing the implied fair value of the reporting unit's goodwill with the carrying amount\rof that goodwill. No amortization is recorded for goodwill with indefinite useful life. No goodwill impairment was recognized during\rthe twelve months ended December 31, 2012 and 2011, respectively. Intangible Assets In accordance withGoodwill and Other Intangible Assets,\rintangible assets that are determined not to have an indefinite useful life are subject to amortization. The Company amortizes\rintangible assets using the straight-line method over their estimated useful lives. Impairment of Long-Lived and Intangible Assets In accordance withAccounting for the Impairment or Disposal\rof Long-Lived Assets, the Company reviews long-lived assets for impairment whenever events or changes in circumstances indicate\rthat the carrying amount of these assets may not be recoverable. The Company assesses the recoverability of the long-lived and\rintangible assets by comparing the carrying amount to the estimated future undiscounted cash flow associated with the related assets.\rNo impairment of intangible assets was recognized during the twelve months ended December 31, 2012 and 2011, respectively. Stock-Based Compensation The Company accounts for stock-based compensation in accordance\rwith the provisions ofShare-Based Payment, which addresses the accounting for equity-based compensation and which requires\rthat the cost of all equity-based compensation arrangements, be reflected in the financial statements over the vesting period based\ron the estimated fair value of the awards. During the twelve months ended December 31, 2012 and 2011, the Company had $210,000\rand zero, respectively, in stock-based compensation expense related to issuances of shares of the Company&#146;s common stock\rto consultants. Treasury Stock We account for treasury stock using the cost method and include\rtreasury stock as a component of shareholders&#146; equity. Other than the share purchases described inNote 3. Equity Transactions,\rwe currently do not have or intend to initiate a share repurchase program. Contingent Consideration &#150; Earn-outs Contingent consideration, the earn-out provisions, which are classified\ras a liability, pursuant to ASC 805, are required to be remeasured to fair value at each reporting date and any changes in fair\rvalue subsequent to the acquisition date are recognized in earnings which could cause a material impact to, and volatility in,\rour operating results. The primary inputs in determining the fair value of the earn-outs that are remeasured to fair value are\rthe quoted price of the underlying shares of our common stock and the probabilities for the three different scenarios in determining\rthe likelihood of common share payouts. Revenue Recognition We recognize revenue in accordance with ASC\r605, &#147;Revenue Recognition,&#148; we recognize as revenue the fees we charge customers as referenced below because\rpersuasive evidence of an arrangement exists, the fees we charge are substantially fixed or determinable during the period that\rwe provide the services, we and our customers understand the specific nature and terms of the agreed upon transactions, collectability\ris reasonable assured and services have been rendered.  The Company and its wholly owned subsidiaries\rrecognize revenue as follows: We generate revenue through attracting internet\rand mobile searchers to our internet properties. The users then frequent our clients who pay us a fee to list on our site. Our Internet properties generate revenues from\rmerchants and advertisers within the industry verticals served. This is the revenue model we employed with WeedMaps.com and is\rthe same revenue model we employ with our current finder sites. The revenue model follows a subscription-based approach, generating\rrecurring monthly revenue from a variety of different package listings, lead generation and advertising. Advertising Package Tiers &#150;For\rour finder sites we typically create advertising package tiers in order to more easily distinguish the different services we offer\rat different price points. The different advertising package tiers also makes it easy for our clients to distinguish which package\rtiers are premium and thus likely to generate more traffic to their brand, product or service. The range of prices we charge for\reach advertising package tier differs per each finder site, per region, and per each tier package. Each region is internally created\rby us based on geographic location, industry density and demographics. Listing Revenue &#150;We generate\rrevenues from fees we charge clients to advertise or list their location, products, and services on one or more of our finder websites.\rWe recognize as revenue the fees we charge customers that advertise or list their related company on our websites. For example, our listing packages typically\rare made up of two groups, Premium Listings and Standard Listings. The most important distinction between Premium Listings and\rStandard Listing packages is typically positioning on our finder websites. This distinction is important because the business that\rappears first in an internet search results list has an increased likelihood of a website visitor clicking on that business and\rthus &#147;converting&#148; the website visitor to a potential customer for our client. In general, being in the top section\rof the search results on any of our finder websites for a given geographical region is deemed preferable because of the increased\rconversion rates (or click-through rates). As a result, we charge a premium dollar amount for a Premium Listing so that the client\ris placed in the top section of search results for a given region. Standard Listing Packages are basic packages\rwhich typically allow a customer to list their brand, product, or service on one or more of our finder sites with the capability\rto edit their listing. A Standard Listing also typically allows a customer to add photos, create a menu, and respond to customer\rreviews, for example. Advertising Revenue &#150;We generate\rrevenues from fees we charge customers for placing ads for their related companies on our websites (i.e. Advertising Packages).\rOur Advertising Packages can include banner ads placed on our finder sites, emails, texts, special promotions, and events. All\rof our Advertising Packages are considered Ad Revenue pursuant to our revenue recognition policy. Content Production Revenue &#150;We\rgenerate revenues from photo and video production of content which is displayed on our finder websites (i.e. Content Production).\rTypically, Content Production that we create on behalf of our clients is considered an add-on or ancillary service. We typically\rcreate video &#147;virtual&#148; tours of our client&#146;s establishments and products, which are then displayed on our finder\rwebsites. We recognize as revenue the fees we charge customers for photo and video production services. All of our Content Production\rservices are considered Content Production Revenue pursuant to our revenue recognition policy. Income Taxes The Company followsAccounting for Income\rTaxesthat requires recognition of deferred income tax liabilities and assets for the expected future tax consequences of temporary\rdifferences between the income tax basis and financial reporting basis of assets and liabilities. Provision for income taxes consists\rof taxes currently due plus deferred taxes. The charge for taxation is based on the results\rfor the year as adjusted for items that are non-assessable or disallowed. It is calculated using tax rates that have been enacted\ror substantively enacted by the balance sheet date. Deferred tax is accounted for using the balance sheet liability method in respect\rof temporary differences arising from differences between the carrying amount of assets and liabilities in the financial statements\rand the corresponding tax basis used in the computation of assessable tax profit. In principle, deferred tax liabilities are recognized\rfor all taxable temporary differences, and deferred tax assets are recognized to the extent that it is probable that taxable profit\rwill be available against which deductible temporary differences can be utilized. Deferred tax is calculated at the tax rates\rthat are expected to apply to the period when the asset is realized or the liability is settled. Deferred tax is charged or credited\rin the income statement, except when it relates to items credited or charged directly to equity, in which case the deferred tax\ris also recorded in equity. Deferred tax assets and liabilities are offset\rwhen they relate to income taxes levied by the same taxation authority and the Company intends to settle its current tax assets\rand liabilities on a net basis. Uncertain tax positions The Company recognizes uncertain tax positions\rbased on a benefit recognition model. Provided that the tax position is deemed more likely than not of being sustained, the Company\rrecognizes the largest amount of tax benefit that is greater than 50 percent likely of being ultimately realized upon settlement.\rThe tax position is derecognized when it is no longer more likely than not of being sustained. The Company classifies income tax-related\rinterest and penalties as interest expense and SGA expense, respectively, on the Consolidated Statement of Operations. Recent Accounting Pronouncements FASB issued an accounting standards update\ramending ASC 220 to improve the comparability, consistency and transparency of reporting of comprehensive income. It amends existing\rguidance by allowing only two options for presenting the components of net income and other comprehensive income: (1) in a single\rcontinuous financial statement, statement of comprehensive income or (2) in two separate but consecutive financial statements,\rconsisting of an income statement followed by a separate statement of other comprehensive income. Also, items that are reclassified\rfrom other comprehensive income to net income must be presented on the face of the financial statements. ASU No. 2011-05 requires\rretrospective application, and it is effective for fiscal years, and interim periods within those years, beginning after December\r15, 2011, with early adoption permitted. In December 2011, FASB issued ASU 2011-12. ASU 2011-12 indefinitely deferred the provisions\rof ASU 2011-05 requiring the presentation of reclassification adjustments on the face of the financial statements for items reclassified\rfrom other comprehensive income to net income. The adoption of this standard did not have a material impact on our financial statements. FASB issued an accounting standards update\ramending ASC 820, which is effective for interim and annual periods beginning after December 31, 2011, to achieve common fair value\rmeasurement and disclosure requirements between GAAP and IFRS. This amendment changes the wording used to describe fair value and\rrequires additional disclosures. The adoption of this amendment did not have a material impact on our financial statements. In September 2011, the FASB issued an amendment\rto an existing accounting standard, which provides an option to perform a qualitative assessment to determine whether further impairment\rtesting on goodwill is necessary. Specifically, an entity has the option to first assess qualitative factors to determine whether\rit is necessary to perform the current two-step test. If an entity believes, as a result of its qualitative assessment, that it\ris more-likely-than-not that the fair value of a reporting unit is less than its carrying amount, the quantitative impairment test\ris required. Otherwise, no further testing is required. This standard is effective for annual and interim goodwill impairment tests\rperformed for fiscal years beginning after December 15, 2011. The adoption of this standard did not have a material impact on our\rfinancial statements. Subsequent Events During May 2009 and February 2010, the FASB\rissued new authoritative pronouncement regarding recognized and non-recognized subsequent events. This guidance establishes general\rstandards of accounting for and disclosure of events that occur after the balance sheet date but before the financial statements\rare issued or are available to be issued. The Company adopted this guidance and it had no impact on the Company&#146;s results\rof operations or financial position. Other Recently Issued, but Not Yet Effective\rAccounting Pronouncements Management does not believe that any other\rrecently issued, but not yet effective accounting pronouncements, if adopted, would have a material effect on the accompanying\rconsolidated financial statements."
