S'Note 2 - summary of significant accounting\rpolicies Basis of Presentation - Unaudited Interim\rFinancial Information The accompanying unaudited interim financial\rstatements and related notes have been prepared in accordance with accounting principles generally accepted in the United States\rof America (&#147;U.S. GAAP&#148;) for interim financial information, and with the rules and regulations of the United States\rSecurities and Exchange Commission (&#147;SEC&#148;) to Form 10-Q and Article 8 of Regulation S-X. Accordingly, they do not include\rall of the information and footnotes required by U.S. GAAP for complete financial statements. The unaudited interim financial\rstatements furnished reflect all adjustments (consisting of normal recurring accruals) which are, in the opinion of management,\rnecessary to a fair statement of the results for the interim periods presented. Unaudited interim results are not necessarily\rindicative of the results for the full fiscal year. These unaudited interim consolidated financial statements should be read in\rconjunction with the financial statements of the Company for the year ended December 31, 2014 and notes thereto contained in the\rinformation as part of the Company&#146;s Annual Report on Form 10-K, which was filed with the Securities and Exchange Commission\ron March 31, 2015. Use of Estimates and Assumptions The preparation of financial statements in\rconformity with accounting principles generally accepted in the United States of America requires management to make estimates\rand assumptions that affect the reported amounts of assets and liabilities and disclosure of contingent assets and liabilities\rat the date of the financial statements and the reported amounts of revenues and expenses during the reporting period. Critical accounting estimates are estimates\rfor which (a) the nature of the estimate is material due to the levels of subjectivity and judgment necessary to account for highly\runcertain matters or the susceptibility of such matters to change and (b) the impact of the estimate on financial condition or\roperating performance is material. The Company&#146;s critical accounting estimates and assumptions affecting the financial statements\rwere:  These significant accounting estimates or\rassumptions bear the risk of change due to the fact that there are uncertainties attached to these estimates or assumptions, and\rcertain estimates or assumptions are difficult to measure or value. Management bases its estimates on historical\rexperience and on various assumptions that are believed to be reasonable in relation to the financial statements taken as a whole\runder the circumstances, the results of which form the basis for making judgments about the carrying values of assets and liabilities\rthat are not readily apparent from other sources. Management regularly evaluates the key factors\rand assumptions used to develop the estimates utilizing currently available information, changes in facts and circumstances, historical\rexperience and reasonable assumptions. After such evaluations, if deemed appropriate, those estimates are adjusted accordingly. Actual results could differ from those estimates. Fair Value of Financial Instruments The Company follows paragraph 825-10-50-10\rof the FASB Accounting Standards Codification for disclosures about fair value of its financial instruments and paragraph 820-10-35-37\rof the FASB Accounting Standards Codification (&#147;Paragraph 820-10-35-37&#148;) to measure the fair value of its financial\rinstruments. Paragraph 820-10-35-37 establishes a framework for measuring fair value in accounting principles generally accepted\rin the United States of America (U.S. GAAP), and expands disclosures about fair value measurements. To increase consistency and\rcomparability in fair value measurements and related disclosures, Paragraph 820-10-35-37 establishes a fair value hierarchy which\rprioritizes the inputs to valuation techniques used to measure fair value into Six (3) broad levels. The fair value hierarchy\rgives the highest priority to quoted prices (unadjusted) in active markets for identical assets or liabilities and the lowest\rpriority to unobservable inputs. The Six (3) levels of fair value hierarchy defined by Paragraph 820-10-35-37 are described below:  Financial assets are considered Level 3 when\rtheir fair values are determined using pricing models, discounted cash flow methodologies or similar techniques and at least one\rsignificant model assumption or input is unobservable. The fair value hierarchy gives the highest\rpriority to quoted prices (unadjusted) in active markets for identical assets or liabilities and the lowest priority to unobservable\rinputs. If the inputs used to measure the financial assets and liabilities fall within more than one level described above, the\rcategorization is based on the lowest level input that is significant to the fair value measurement of the instrument. The carrying amount of the Company&#146;s\rfinancial assets and liabilities, such as cash, prepaid expenses, accounts payable and accrued expenses approximate their fair\rvalue because of the short maturity of those instruments. Transactions involving related parties cannot\rbe presumed to be carried out on an arm&#146;s-length basis, as the requisite conditions of competitive, free-market dealings\rmay not exist. Representations about transactions with related parties, if made, shall not imply that the related party transactions\rwere consummated on terms equivalent to those that prevail in arm&#146;s-length transactions unless such representations can be\rsubstantiated. The Company includes fair value information\rin the notes to financial statements when the fair value of its financial instruments is different from the book value. When the\rbook value approximates fair value, no additional disclosure is made. Valuation of Derivatives The Company evaluates its convertible instruments,\roptions, warrants or other contracts to determine if those contracts or embedded components of those contracts qualify as derivatives\rto be separately accounted for under ASC Topic 815, &#147;Derivatives and Hedging.&#148; The result of this accounting treatment\ris that the fair value of the derivative is marked-to-market each balance sheet date. The change in fair value is recorded in\rthe statement of operations as other income (expense). Upon conversion or exercise of a derivative instrument, the instrument\ris marked to fair value at the conversion date and then that fair value is reclassified to equity. Equity instruments that are\rinitially classified as equity that become subject to reclassification under ASC Topic 815 are reclassified to liabilities at\rthe fair value of the instrument on the reclassification date. We analyzed the derivative financial instruments in accordance\rwith ASC 815. The objective is to provide guidance for determining whether an equity-linked financial instrument is indexed to\ran entity&#146;s own stock. This determination is needed for a scope exception which would enable a derivative instrument to be\raccounted for under the accrual method. The classification of a non-derivative instrument that falls within the scope of ASC 815-40-05\r&#147;Accounting for Derivative Financial Instruments Indexed to, and Potentially Settled in, a Company&#146;s Own Stock&#148;\ralso hinges on whether the instrument is indexed to an entity&#146;s own stock. A non-derivative instrument that is not indexed\rto an entity&#146;s own stock cannot be classified as equity and must be accounted for as a liability. There is a two-step approach\rin determining whether an instrument or embedded feature is indexed to an entity&#146;s own stock. First, the instrument&#146;s\rcontingent exercise provisions, if any, must be evaluated, followed by an evaluation of the instrument&#146;s settlement provisions.\rThe Company utilized multinomial lattice models that value the derivative liability based on a probability weighted discounted\rcash flow model. The Company utilized the fair value standard set forth by the Financial Accounting Standards Board, defined as\rthe amount at which the assets (or liability) could be bought (or incurred) or sold (or settled) in a current transaction between\rwilling parties, that is, other than in a forced or liquidation sale. The derivative liabilities result in a reduction\rof the initial carrying amount (as unamortized discount) of the Convertible Notes. This derivative liability is marked-to-market\reach quarter with the change in fair value recorded in the income statement. Unamortized discount is amortized to interest expense\rusing the effective interest method over the life of the Convertible Note. Fair Value of Financial Instruments The Company includes fair value information\rin the notes to financial statements when the fair value of its financial instruments is different from the book value. When the\rbook value approximates fair value, no additional disclosure is made. Cash Equivalents The Company considers all highly liquid investments\rwith a maturity of three months or less to be cash and cash equivalents. Accounts Receivable and Allowance for\rDoubtful Accounts Accounts receivable are recorded at the invoiced\ramount, net of an allowance for doubtful accounts. The Company follows paragraph 310-10-50-9 of the FASB Accounting Standards\rCodification to estimate the allowance for doubtful accounts. The Company performs on-going credit evaluations of its customers\rand adjusts credit limits based upon payment history and the customer&#146;s current credit worthiness, as determined by the review\rof their current credit information; and determines the allowance for doubtful accounts based on historical write-off experience,\rcustomer specific facts and general economic conditions that may affect a client&#146;s ability to pay. Pursuant to paragraph 310-10-50-2 of the FASB\rAccounting Standards Codification account balances are charged off against the allowance after all means of collection have been\rexhausted and the potential for recovery is considered remote. The Company has adopted paragraph 310-10-50-6 of the FASB Accounting\rStandards Codification and determine when receivables are past due or delinquent based on how recently payments have been received. Outstanding account balances are reviewed\rindividually for collectability. The allowance for doubtful accounts is the Company&#146;s best estimate of the amount of probable\rcredit losses in the Company&#146;s existing accounts receivable. Bad debt expense is included in general and administrative expenses,\rif any. There was no allowance for doubtful accounts\rat December 31, 2015 or December 31, 2014. The Company does not have any off-balance-sheet\rcredit exposure to its customers at December 31, 2015 or December 31, 2014. Furniture and Fixtures Furniture and fixtures are recorded at cost.\rExpenditures for major additions and betterments are capitalized. Maintenance and repairs are charged to operations as incurred.\rDepreciation is computed by the straight-line method (after taking into account their respective estimated residual values) over\rthe estimated useful lives of the respective assets as follows:  Upon sale or retirement, the related cost\rand accumulated depreciation are removed from the accounts and any gain or loss is reflected in the statements of operations. Related Parties The Company follows subtopic 850-10 of the\rFASB Accounting Standards Codification for the identification of related parties and disclosure of related party transactions. Pursuant to Section 850-10-20 the Related\rparties include: a. affiliates of the Company (&#147;Affiliate&#148; means, with respect to any specified Person, any other Person\rthat, directly or indirectly through one or more intermediaries, controls, is controlled by or is under common control with such\rPerson, as such terms are used in and construed under Rule 405 under the Securities Act); b. entities for which investments in\rtheir equity securities would be required, absent the election of the fair value option under the Fair Value Option Subsection\rof Section 825-10-15, to be accounted for by the equity method by the investing entity; c. trusts for the benefit of employees,\rsuch as pension and profit-sharing trusts that are managed by or under the trusteeship of management; d. principal owners of the\rCompany; e. management of the Company; f. other parties with which the Company may deal if one party controls or can significantly\rinfluence the management or operating policies of the other to an extent that one of the transacting parties might be prevented\rfrom fully pursuing its own separate interests; and g. other parties that can significantly influence the management or operating\rpolicies of the transacting parties or that have an ownership interest in one of the transacting parties and can significantly\rinfluence the other to an extent that one or more of the transacting parties might be prevented from fully pursuing its own separate\rinterests. The financial statements shall include disclosures\rof material related party transactions, other than compensation arrangements, expense allowances, and other similar items in the\rordinary course of business. However, disclosure of transactions that are eliminated in the preparation of financial statements\ris not required in those statements. The disclosures shall include: a. the nature of the relationship(s) involved; b. a description\rof the transactions, including transactions to which no amounts or nominal amounts were ascribed, for each of the periods for\rwhich income statements are presented, and such other information deemed necessary to an understanding of the effects of the transactions\ron the financial statements; c. the dollar amounts of transactions for each of the periods for which income statements are presented\rand the effects of any change in the method of establishing the terms from that used in the preceding period; and d. a amounts\rdue from or to related parties as of the date of each balance sheet presented and, if not otherwise apparent, the terms and manner\rof settlement. Commitments and contingencies The Company follows subtopic 450-20 of the\rFASB Accounting Standards Codification to report accounting for contingencies. Certain conditions may exist as of the date the\rfinancial statements are issued, which may result in a loss to the Company but which will only be resolved when one or more future\revents occur or fail to occur. The Company assesses such contingent liabilities, and such assessment inherently involves an exercise\rof judgment. In assessing loss contingencies related to legal proceedings that are pending against the Company or unasserted claims\rthat may result in such proceedings, the Company evaluates the perceived merits of any legal proceedings or unasserted claims\ras well as the perceived merits of the amount of relief sought or expected to be sought therein. If the assessment of a contingency indicates\rthat it is probable that a material loss has been incurred and the amount of the liability can be estimated, then the estimated\rliability would be accrued in the Company&#146;s financial statements. If the assessment indicates that a potential material loss\rcontingency is not probable but is reasonably possible, or is probable but cannot be estimated, then the nature of the contingent\rliability, and an estimate of the range of possible losses, if determinable and material, would be disclosed. Loss contingencies considered remote are generally\rnot disclosed unless they involve guarantees, in which case the guarantees would be disclosed. Revenue Recognition The Company applies paragraph 605-10-S99-1\rof the FASB Accounting Standards Codification for revenue recognition. The Company recognizes revenue when it is realized or realizable\rand earned. The Company considers revenue realized or realizable and earned when all of the following criteria are met: (i) persuasive\revidence of an arrangement exists, (ii) the product has been shipped or the services have been rendered to the customer, (iii)\rthe sales price is fixed or determinable, and (iv) collectability is reasonably assured. The Company derives its revenues from sales\rcontracts with its customer with revenues being generated upon rendering of services. Persuasive evidence of an arrangement is\rdemonstrated via invoice; service is considered provided when the service is delivered to the customers; and the sales price to\rthe customer is fixed upon acceptance of the purchase order and there is no separate sales rebate, discount, or volume incentive. Equity Instruments Issued to Parties\rOther Than Employees for Acquiring Goods or Services The Company accounts for equity instruments\rissued to parties other than employees for acquiring goods or services under the guidance of Sub-topic 505-50 of the FASB Accounting\rStandards Codification (&#147;Sub-topic 505-50&#148;). Pursuant to ASC paragraph 505-50-25-7, if\rfully vested, non-forfeitable equity instruments are issued at the date the grantor and grantee enter into an agreement for goods\ror services (no specific performance is required by the grantee to retain those equity instruments), then, because of the elimination\rof any obligation on the part of the counterparty to earn the equity instruments, a measurement date has been reached. A grantor\rshall recognize the equity instruments when they are issued (in most cases, when the agreement is entered into). Whether the corresponding\rcost is an immediate expense or a prepaid asset (or whether the debit should be characterized as contra-equity under the requirements\rof paragraph 505-50-45-1) depends on the specific facts and circumstances. Pursuant to ASC paragraph 505-50-45-1, a grantor may\rconclude that an asset (other than a note or a receivable) has been received in return for fully vested, non-forfeitable equity\rinstruments that are issued at the date the grantor and grantee enter into an agreement for goods or services (and no specific\rperformance is required by the grantee in order to retain those equity instruments). Such an asset shall not be displayed as contra-equity\rby the grantor of the equity instruments. The transferability (or lack thereof) of the equity instruments shall not affect the\rbalance sheet display of the asset. This guidance is limited to transactions in which equity instruments are transferred to other\rthan employees in exchange for goods or services. Pursuant to Paragraphs 505-50-25-8 and 505-50-25-9,\ran entity may grant fully vested, non-forfeitable equity instruments that are exercisable by the grantee only after a specified\rperiod of time if the terms of the agreement provide for earlier exercisability if the grantee achieves specified performance\rconditions. Any measured cost of the transaction shall be recognized in the same period(s) and in the same manner as if the entity\rhad paid cash for the goods or services or used cash rebates as a sales discount instead of paying with, or using, the equity\rinstruments. A recognized asset, expense, or sales discount shall not be reversed if a stock option that the counterparty has\rthe right to exercise expires unexercised. Pursuant to ASC Paragraphs 505-50-30-2 and\r505-50-30-11 share-based payment transactions with non-employees shall be measured at the fair value of the consideration received\ror the fair value of the equity instruments issued, whichever is more reliably measurable. The issuer shall measure the fair value\rof the equity instruments in these transactions using the stock price and other measurement assumptions as of the earlier of the\rfollowing dates, referred to as the measurement date: (a) The date at which a commitment for performance by the counterparty to\rearn the equity instruments is reached (a performance commitment); or (b) The date at which the counterparty&#146;s performance\ris complete. If the Company&#146;s common shares are traded in one of the national exchanges the grant-date share price of the\rCompany&#146;s common stock will be used to measure the fair value of the common shares issued, however, if the Company&#146;s\rcommon shares are thinly traded the use of share prices established in the Company&#146;s most recent private placement memorandum\r(&#147;PPM&#148;), or weekly or monthly price observations would generally be more appropriate than the use of daily price observations\ras such shares could be artificially inflated due to a larger spread between the bid and asked quotes and lack of consistent trading\rin the market. Pursuant to ASC Paragraph 718-10-55-21 if\ran observable market price is not available for a share option or similar instrument with the same or similar terms and conditions,\ran entity shall estimate the fair value of that instrument using a valuation technique or model that meets the requirements in\rparagraph 718-10-55-11 and takes into account, at a minimum, all of the following factors:   Pursuant to ASC paragraph 505-50-S99-1, if\rthe Company receives a right to receive future services in exchange for unvested, forfeitable equity instruments, those equity\rinstruments are treated as unissued for accounting purposes until the future services are received (that is, the instruments are\rnot considered issued until they vest). Consequently, there would be no recognition at the measurement date and no entry should\rbe recorded. Stock-Based Compensation The Company records stock-based compensation\rin accordance with FASB ASC Topic 718, &#147;Compensation &#150; Stock Compensation.&#148; FASB ASC Topic 718 requires\rcompanies to measure compensation cost for stock-based employee compensation at fair value at the grant date and recognize the\rexpense over the employee&#146;s requisite service period. The Company recognizes in the statement of operations the grant-date\rfair value of stock options and other equity-based compensation issued to employees and non-employees. There were 6,000,000 options\routstanding as of December 31, 2015. Research and Development The Company follows paragraph 730-10-25-1\rof the FASB Accounting Standards Codification (formerly Statement of Financial Accounting Standards No. 2&#147;Accounting\rfor Research and Development Costs&#148;) and paragraph 730-20-25-11 of the FASB Accounting Standards Codification (formerly\rStatement of Financial Accounting Standards No. 68&#147;Research and Development Arrangements&#148;) for research and\rdevelopment costs. Research and development costs are charged to expense as incurred. Research and development costs consist primarily\rof remuneration for research and development staff, depreciation and maintenance expenses of research and development equipment,\rmaterial and testing costs for research and development as well as research and development arrangements with unrelated third\rparty research and development institutions. Deferred Tax Assets and Income Tax Provision The Company accounts for income taxes under\rSection 740-10-30 of the FASB Accounting Standards Codification, which requires recognition of deferred tax assets and liabilities\rfor the expected future tax consequences of events that have been included in the financial statements or tax returns. Under this\rmethod, deferred tax assets and liabilities are based on the differences between the financial statement and tax bases of assets\rand liabilities using enacted tax rates in effect for the year in which the differences are expected to reverse. Deferred tax\rassets are reduced by a valuation allowance to the extent management concludes it is more likely than not that the assets will\rnot be realized. Deferred tax assets and liabilities are measured\rusing enacted tax rates expected to apply to taxable income in the years in which those temporary differences are expected to\rbe recovered or settled. The effect on deferred tax assets and liabilities of a change in tax rates is recognized in the statements\rof operations in the period that includes the enactment date. The Company adopted the provisions of paragraph\r740-10-25-13 of the FASB Accounting Standards Codification. Paragraph 740-10-25-13 addresses the determination of whether tax\rbenefits claimed or expected to be claimed on a tax return should be recorded in the financial statements. Under paragraph 740-10-25-13,\rthe Company may recognize the tax benefit from an uncertain tax position only if it is more likely than not that the tax position\rwill be sustained on examination by the taxing authorities, based on the technical merits of the position. The tax benefits recognized\rin the financial statements from such a position should be measured based on the largest benefit that has a greater than fifty\rpercent (50%) likelihood of being realized upon ultimate settlement. Paragraph 740-10-25-13 also provides guidance on de-recognition,\rclassification, interest and penalties on income taxes, accounting in interim periods and requires increased disclosures. The estimated future tax effects of temporary\rdifferences between the tax basis of assets and liabilities are reported in the accompanying balance sheets, as well as tax credit\rcarry-backs and carry-forwards. The Company periodically reviews the recoverability of deferred tax assets recorded on its balance\rsheets and provides valuation allowances as management deems necessary. Management makes judgments as to the interpretation\rof the tax laws that might be challenged upon an audit and cause changes to previous estimates of tax liability. In addition,\rthe Company operates within multiple taxing jurisdictions and is subject to audit in these jurisdictions. In management&#146;s\ropinion, adequate provisions for income taxes have been made for all years. If actual taxable income by tax jurisdiction varies\rfrom estimates, additional allowances or reversals of reserves may be necessary. Tax years that remain subject to examination\rby major tax jurisdictions The Company discloses tax years that remain\rsubject to examination by major tax jurisdictions pursuant to the ASC Paragraph 740-10-50-15. Earnings per Share Earnings Per Share (&#147;EPS&#148;) is\rthe amount of earnings attributable to each share of common stock. For convenience, the term is used to refer to either earnings\ror loss per share. EPS is computed pursuant to section 260-10-45 of the FASB Accounting Standards Codification. Pursuant to ASC\rParagraphs 260-10-45-10 through 260-10-45-16 Basic EPS shall be computed by dividing income available to common stockholders (the\rnumerator) by the weighted-average number of common shares outstanding (the denominator) during the period. Income available to\rcommon stockholders shall be computed by deducting both the dividends declared in the period on preferred stock (whether or not\rpaid) and the dividends accumulated for the period on cumulative preferred stock (whether or not earned) from income from continuing\roperations (if that amount appears in the income statement) and also from net income. The computation of diluted EPS is similar\rto the computation of basic EPS except that the denominator is increased to include the number of additional common shares that\rwould have been outstanding if the dilutive potential common shares had been issued during the period to reflect the potential\rdilution that could occur from common shares issuable through contingent shares issuance arrangement, stock options or warrants. Pursuant to ASC Paragraphs 260-10-45-45-21\rthrough 260-10-45-45-23 Diluted EPS shall be based on the most advantageous conversion rate or exercise price from the standpoint\rof the security holder. The dilutive effect of outstanding call options and warrants (and their equivalents) issued by the reporting\rentity shall be reflected in diluted EPS by application of the treasury stock method unless the provisions of paragraphs 260-10-45-35\rthrough 45-36 and 260-10-55-8 through 55-11 require that another method be applied. Equivalents of options and warrants include\rnon-vested stock granted to employees, stock purchase contracts, and partially paid stock subscriptions (see paragraph 260-10-55-23).\rAnti-dilutive contracts, such as purchased put options and purchased call options, shall be excluded from diluted EPS. Under the\rtreasury stock method: a. Exercise of options and warrants shall be assumed at the beginning of the period (or at time of issuance,\rif later) and common shares shall be assumed to be issued. b. The proceeds from exercise shall be assumed to be used to purchase\rcommon stock at the average market price during the period. (See paragraphs 260-10-45-29 and 260-10-55-4 through 55-5.) c. The\rincremental shares (the difference between the number of shares assumed issued and the number of shares assumed purchased) shall\rbe included in the denominator of the diluted EPS computation. The computation of basic and diluted loss\rper share for the years ended December 31, 2015 and 2014 excludes the common stock equivalents of the following potentially dilutive\rsecurities because their inclusion would be anti-dilutive: &#9679;   Stock Warrants (Exercise\rprice - $0.2625/share) &#150; 850,000 common stock equivalents&#9679;   Convertible Debt\r(Exercise price - $0.2625/share) &#150; 1,804,515 common stock equivalents There were no potentially dilutive shares outstanding for the reporting\ryear ended December 31, 2014. Cash Flows Reporting The Company adopted paragraph 230-10-45-24\rof the FASB Accounting Standards Codification for cash flows reporting, classifies cash receipts and payments according to whether\rthey stem from operating, investing, or financing activities and provides definitions of each category, and uses the indirect\ror reconciliation method (&#147;Indirect method&#148;) as defined by paragraph 230-10-45-25 of the FASB Accounting Standards Codification\rto report net cash flow from operating activities by adjusting net income to reconcile it to net cash flow from operating activities\rby removing the effects of (a) all deferrals of past operating cash receipts and payments and all accruals of expected future\roperating cash receipts and payments and (b) all items that are included in net income that do not affect operating cash receipts\rand payments. The Company reports the reporting currency equivalent of foreign currency cash flows, using the current exchange\rrate at the time of the cash flows and the effect of exchange rate changes on cash held in foreign currencies is reported as a\rseparate item in the reconciliation of beginning and ending balances of cash and cash equivalents and separately provides information\rabout investing and financing activities not resulting in cash receipts or payments in the period pursuant to paragraph 830-230-45-1\rof the FASB Accounting Standards Codification. Subsequent Events The Company follows the guidance in Section\r855-10-50 of the FASB Accounting Standards Codification for the disclosure of subsequent events. The Company will evaluate subsequent\revents through the date when the financial statements were issued. Pursuant to ASU 2010-09 of the FASB Accounting Standards Codification,\rthe Company as an SEC filer considers its financial statements issued when they are widely distributed to users, such as through\rfiling them on EDGAR. Recently issued accounting pronouncements In May 2014, the FASB issued the FASB Accounting\rStandards Update No. 2014-09 &#147;Revenue from Contracts with Customers (Topic 606)&#148; (&#147;ASU 2014-09&#148;) This guidance amends the existing FASB Accounting\rStandards Codification, creating a new Topic 606,Revenue from Contracts with Customer.The core principle of the guidance\ris that an entity should recognize revenue to depict the transfer of promised goods or services to customers in an amount that\rreflects the consideration to which the entity expects to be entitled in exchange for those goods or services. To achieve that core principle, an entity\rshould apply the following steps:  The ASU also provides guidance on disclosures\rthat should be provided to enable financial statement users to understand the nature, amount, timing, and uncertainty of revenue\rrecognition and cash flows arising from contracts with customers. Qualitative and quantitative information is required about the\rfollowing:  ASU 2014-09 is effective for periods beginning\rafter December 15, 2016, including interim reporting periods within that reporting period for all public entities. Early application\ris not permitted. In June 2014, the FASB issued the FASB Accounting\rStandards Update No. 2014-12 &#147;Compensation-Stock Compensation (Topic 718):Accounting for Share-Based Payments\rWhen the Terms of an Award Provide That a Performance Target Could Be Achieved after the Requisite Service Period&#148; (&#147;ASU\r2014-12&#148;). The amendments clarify the proper method of\raccounting for share-based payments when the terms of an award provide that a performance target could be achieved after the requisite\rservice period. The Update requires that a performance target that affects vesting and that could be achieved after the requisite\rservice period be treated as a performance condition. The performance target should not be reflected in estimating the grant-date\rfair value of the award. Compensation cost should be recognized in the period in which it becomes probable that the performance\rtarget will be achieved and should represent the compensation cost attributable to the period(s) for which the requisite service\rhas already been rendered. The amendments in this Update are effective\rfor annual periods and interim periods within those annual periods beginning after December 15, 2015. Earlier adoption is permitted\rand the Company has elected to implement the guidance in its quarter ended September 30, 2014. In August 2014, the FASB issued the FASB Accounting\rStandards Update No. 2014-15 &#147;Presentation of Financial Statements-Going Concern (Subtopic 205-40): Disclosure of Uncertainties\rabout an Entity&#146;s Ability to Continue as a Going Concern (&#147;ASU 2014-15&#148;). In connection with preparing financial statements\rfor each annual and interim reporting period, an entity&#146;s management should evaluate whether there are conditions or events,\rconsidered in the aggregate, that raise substantial doubt about the entity&#146;s ability to continue as a going concern within\rone year after the date that the financial statements are issued (or within one year after the date that the financial statements\rare available to be issued when applicable). Management&#146;s evaluation should be based on relevant conditions and events that\rare known and reasonably knowable at the date that the financial statements are issued (or at the date that the financial statements\rare available to be issued when applicable). Substantial doubt about an entity&#146;s ability to continue as a going concern exists\rwhen relevant conditions and events, considered in the aggregate, indicate that it is probable that the entity will be unable\rto meet its obligations as they become due within one year after the date that the financial statements are issued (or available\rto be issued). The term probable is used consistently with its use in Topic 450, Contingencies. When management identifies conditions or events\rthat raise substantial doubt about an entity&#146;s ability to continue as a going concern, management should consider whether\rits plans that are intended to mitigate those relevant conditions or events will alleviate the substantial doubt. The mitigating\reffect of management&#146;s plans should be considered only to the extent that (1) it is probable that the plans will be effectively\rimplemented and, if so, (2) it is probable that the plans will mitigate the conditions or events that raise substantial doubt\rabout the entity&#146;s ability to continue as a going concern. If conditions or events raise substantial\rdoubt about an entity&#146;s ability to continue as a going concern, but the substantial doubt is alleviated as a result of consideration\rof management&#146;s plans, the entity should disclose information that enables users of the financial statements to understand\rall of the following (or refer to similar information disclosed elsewhere in the footnotes):  If conditions or events raise substantial\rdoubt about an entity&#146;s ability to continue as a going concern, and substantial doubt is not alleviated after consideration\rof management&#146;s plans, an entity should include a statement in the footnotes indicating that there is substantial doubt about\rthe entity&#146;s ability to continue as a going concern within one year after the date that the financial statements are issued\r(or available to be issued). Additionally, the entity should disclose information that enables users of the financial statements\rto understand all of the following:  The amendments in this Update are effective\rfor the annual period ending after December 15, 2016, and for annual periods and interim periods thereafter. Early application\ris permitted. In November 2014, the FASB issued the FASB\rAccounting Standards Update No. 2014-16 &#147;Derivatives and Hedging (Topic 815):Determining Whether the Host Contract\rin a Hybrid Financial Instrument Issued in the Form of a Share Is More Akin to Debt or to Equity&#148; (&#147;ASU 2014-16&#148;).The amendments in ASU No. 2014-16 clarify that an entity must take into account all relevant terms and features when reviewing\rthe nature of the host contract. Additionally, the amendments state that no one term or feature would define the host contract&#146;s\reconomic characteristics and risks. Instead, the economic characteristics and risks of the hybrid financial instrument as a whole\rwould determine the nature of the host contract. The amendments in this Update are effective for public business entities for\rfiscal years, and interim periods within those fiscal years, beginning after December 15, 2015. Early adoption, including adoption\rin an interim period, is permitted. In January 2015, the FASB issued the FASB\rAccounting Standards Update No. 2015-01 &#147;Income Statement-Extraordinary and Unusual Items (Subtopic 225-20):Simplifying\rIncome Statement Presentation by Eliminating the Concept of Extraordinary Items&#148; (&#147;ASU 2015-01&#148;).This Update\reliminates from GAAP the concept of extraordinary items and the requirements in Subtopic 225-20 for reporting entities to separately\rclassify, present, and disclose extraordinary events and transactions. The amendments in this Update are effective for fiscal\ryears, and interim periods within those fiscal years, beginning after December 15, 2015. Early adoption is permitted provided\rthat the guidance is applied from the beginning of the fiscal year of adoption. The amendments in this Update are effective\rfor public business entities for fiscal years, and for interim periods within those fiscal years, beginning after December 15,\r2015. Early adoption is permitted, including adoption in an interim period. In August, 2015, the FASB issued ASU No. 2015-14,Revenue from Contracts with Customers (Topic 606): Deferral of the Effective Date.The amendment in this ASU defers the\reffective date of ASU No. 2014-09 for all entities for one year. Public business entities, certain not-for-profit entities, and\rcertain employee benefit plans should apply the guidance in ASU 2014-09 to annual reporting periods beginning December 15, 2017,\rincluding interim reporting periods within that reporting period. Earlier application is permitted only as of annual reporting\rperiods beginning after December 31, 2016, including interim reporting periods with that reporting period. In November 2015, the FASB issued ASU No.\r2015-17,Income Taxes (Topic 740). &#145;The amendments in ASU 2015-17 eliminates the current requirement for organizations\rto present deferred tax liabilities and assets as current and noncurrent in a classified balance sheet. Instead, organizations\rwill be required to classify all deferred tax assets and liabilities as noncurrent. ASU 2015-17 is effective for public business\rentities for financial statements issued for annual periods beginning after December 15, 2016, and interim periods within those\rannual periods. The amendments may be applied prospectively to all deferred tax liabilities and assets or retrospectively to all\rperiods presented. Management does not believe that any other\rrecently issued, but not yet effective accounting pronouncements, if adopted, would have a material effect on the accompanying\rfinancial statements.'
