S'(A)Nature of OperationsRemmington Enterprises, Inc. (an exploration\rstage company) (the "Company") was incorporated under the laws of the State of Nevada on July 15, 2011. Remmington Enterprises,\rInc. is a precious metal mineral acquisition, exploration and development company. (B) Basis of PresentationThe Company is in the exploration stage\rin accordance with Accounting Standards Codification (&#147;ASC&#148;) Topic No. 915. These financial statements have been prepared\rin conformity with generally accepted accounting principles in the United States of America and include the have been consistently\rapplied in the preparation of the financial statements on a going concern basis, which assumes the realization of assets and the\rdischarge of liabilities in the normal course of operations for the foreseeable future. The Company has adopted a July 31 year\rend. (C) Use of EstimatesIn preparing financial statements in conformity\rwith generally accepted accounting principles, management is required to make estimates and assumptions that affect the reported\ramounts of assets and liabilities and the disclosure of contingent assets and liabilities at the date of the financial statements\rand expenses during the reported period. Actual results could differ from those estimates. (D) Cash and Cash EquivalentsThe Company considers all highly liquid\rtemporary cash investments with an original maturity of three months or less to be cash equivalents. At July 31, 2012, the Company\rhad no cash equivalents. (E) Exploration and Development CostsIn general, exploration costs are expensed\ras incurred. When the Company has determined that a mineral property can be economically developed as a result of establishing\rproven and probable reserves, the costs incurred to develop such property are capitalized. Costs incurred to maintain current production\ror to maintain assets on a standby basis are charged to operations. Costs of abandoned projects are charged to operations upon\rabandonment. During the year ended July 31, 2012, the Company recorded exploration costs of $560. (F) Impairment of Long-Lived AssetsThe Company accounts for its long-lived\rassets in accordance with ASC Topic 360-10. ASC Topic 360-10 requires that long-lived assets be reviewed for impairment whenever\revents or changes in circumstances indicate that the historical cost carrying value of an asset may no longer be appropriate. The\rCompany assesses recoverability of the carrying value of an asset by estimating the future net cash flows expected to result from\rthe asset, including eventual disposition. If the future net cash flows are less than the carrying value of the asset, an impairment\rloss is recorded equal to the difference between the asset\'s carrying value and fair value or disposable value. During the period\rended July 31, 2012, no impairment was recognized. (G) Financial InstrumentsFinancial instruments consist of cash,\raccounts receivable, accounts payable, notes payable and advances payable. Recorded values of cash, receivables, accounts payable\rand accrued liabilities approximate fair values due to the short maturities of such instruments. Recorded values for notes payable\rand related liabilities approximate fair values, since their stated or imputed interest rates are commensurate with prevailing\rmarket rates for similar obligations. (H) Loss Per ShareThe Company reports earnings (loss) per\rshare in accordance with ASC Topic 260-10. Basic earnings (loss) per share is computed by dividing income (loss) available to common\rshareholders by the weighted average number of common shares available. Diluted earnings (loss) per share is computed similar to\rbasic earnings (loss) per share except that the denominator is increased to include the number of additional common shares that\rwould have been outstanding if the potential common shares had been issued and if the additional common shares were dilutive. As\rof July 31, 2012, there were no potential common shares underlying warrants or options. (I) Revenue RecognitionThe Company currently has not generated\rrevenues. Any future revenues earned, primarily through the sale of extracted minerals, will be recognized utilizing the following\rgeneral revenue recognition criteria: 1) pervasive evidence of an arrangement exists; 2) delivery has occurred; 3) the price to\rthe buyer is fixed or determinable; and 4) collectability is reasonably assured. Delivery on mineral sales is determined\rto be complete for revenue recognition purposes when title and risk of loss has passed to the customer in accordance with stated\rcontractual terms and there is no future obligations related to the shipment. Title generally passes as the minerals are loaded\rinto transport carriers for delivery to the customer. (J) Income TaxesIncome taxes are accounted for under the\rasset and liability method in accordance with ASC Topic 740-10. Deferred tax assets and liabilities are recognized for the future\rtax consequences attributable to differences between the financial statement carrying amounts of existing assets and liabilities\rand their respective tax bases and operating loss carryforwards. Deferred tax assets and liabilities are measured using enacted\rtax rates expected to apply to taxable income in the years in which those temporary differences are expected to be recovered or\rsettled. The effect on deferred tax assets and liabilities of a change in tax rates is recognized in income in the period that\rincludes the enactment date. When it is considered to be more likely than not that a deferred tax asset will not be realized, a\rvaluation allowance is provided for the excess. (K) New Accounting StandardsWe do not believe there\rare any recently issued accounting standards that have not yet been adopted that will have a material impact on the Company&#146;s\rfinancial statements.'
