S'Note\r2 &#150; SUMMARY OF SIGNIFICANT ACCOUNTING POLICIES Basis\rof Presentation The\raccompanying consolidated financial statements are prepared in accordance with accounting principles generally accepted in the\rUnited States of America (&#147;US GAAP&#148;) and pursuant to the rules and regulations of the Securities and Exchange Commission\r(&#147;SEC&#148;). Principles\rof Consolidation The\rconsolidated financial statements include the accounts of FlikMedia, Inc. and its wholly owned subsidiary Flikdate, Inc. All inter-company\raccounts and transactions have been eliminated in the preparation of these consolidated statements. Use\rof Estimates The\rpreparation of financial statements in conformity with generally accepted accounting principles requires management to make estimates\rand assumptions that affect the reported amounts of assets and liabilities and the disclosure of contingent assets and liabilities\rat the date of the financial statements and the reported amounts of revenues and expenses during the reporting period. Actual\rresults could differ from those estimates. Estimates and assumptions are reviewed periodically and the effects of revisions are\rreflected in the consolidated financial statements in the period they are determined. Cash\rand Cash Equivalents Cash\rand equivalents include cash in hand and cash in demand deposits, certificates of deposit and all highly liquid debt instruments\rwith original maturities of three months or less. Income\rTaxes The\rCompany accounts for income taxes in accordance with FASB ASC 740, &#147;Income Taxes&#148;. Under FASB ASC 740, deferred income\rtaxes are recognized for the tax consequences in future years of differences between the tax bases of assets and liabilities and\rtheir financial statement reporting amounts at each period end based on enacted tax laws and statutory tax rates applicable to\rthe periods in which the differences are expected to affect taxable income. Valuation allowances are established, when necessary,\rto reduce deferred tax assets to the amount expected to be realized. The provision for income taxes represents the tax expense\rfor the period, if any, and the change during the period in deferred tax assets and liabilities. The\rCompany has significant income tax net operating losses; however, due to the uncertainty of the realize-ability of the related\rdeferred tax asset and other deferred tax assets, a valuation allowance equal to the amount of deferred tax assets has been established\rat December 31, 2014 and 2013. FASB\rASC 740 also provides criteria for the recognition, measurement, presentation and disclosure of uncertain tax positions. A tax\rbenefit from an uncertain position may be recognized only if it is &#147;more likely than not&#148; that the position is sustainable\rbased on its technical merit. The\rCompany&#146;s federal and state income tax returns for the tax years 2011, 2012 and 2013 remain subject to examination for federal\rand state taxes. Fair\rValue of Financial Instruments Disclosures\rabout fair value of financial instruments require disclosure of the fair value information, whether or not recognized in our consolidated\rbalance sheet, where it is practicable to estimate that value. As of December 31, 2014, the amounts reported for cash, accrued\rliabilities and accrued interest approximated fair value because of their short maturities. In\raccordance with ASC Topic 820, &#147;Fair Value Measurements and Disclosures,&#148; we measure certain financial instruments at\rfair value on a recurring basis. ASC Topic 820 defines fair value, established a framework for measuring fair value in accordance\rwith accounting principles generally accepted in the United States, and expands disclosures about fair value measurements. Fair\rvalue is defined as the price that would be received to sell an asset or paid to transfer a liability in an orderly transaction\rbetween market participants at the measurement date. ASC Topic 820 established a three-tier fair value hierarchy, which prioritizes\rthe inputs used in measuring fair value. The hierarchy gives the highest priority to unadjusted quoted prices in active markets\rfor identical assets or liabilities (level 1 measurements) and the lowest priority to unobservable inputs (level 3 measurements).\rThese tiers include:  Property&#38;\requipment Property\rand equipment is stated at cost and depreciated using the straight-line method over the shorter of the estimated useful life of\rthe asset or the lease term. The estimated useful lives of our property and equipment are generally as follows:  Furniture\rand equipment consisted of the following at December 31, 2014 and 2013:  For\rthe years ended December 31, 2014 and 2013, depreciation expense was $1,022 and $257, respectively. Intangible\rAssets The\rCompany records identifiable intangible assets at fair value on the date of acquisition and evaluates the useful life of each\rasset. Finite-lived intangible assets primarily consist of software development capitalized. Finite-lived intangible assets are\ramortized on a straight-line basis and are tested for recoverability if events or changes in circumstances indicate that their\rcarrying amounts may not be recoverable. These intangibles have useful lives ranging from 1 to 10 years. No events or changes\rin circumstances indicate that impairment existed as of December 31, 2014. Valuation\rof Long-Lived Assets Long-lived\rassets include equipment and intangible assets other than those with indefinite lives. We assess the carrying value of our long-lived\rasset groups when indicators of impairment exist and recognize an impairment loss when the carrying amount of a long-lived asset\ris not recoverable from the undiscounted cash flows expected to result from the use and eventual disposition of the asset. Indicators\rof impairment include significant underperformance relative to historical or projected future operating results, significant changes\rin our use of the assets or in our business strategy, loss of or changes in customer relationships and significant negative industry\ror economic trends. When indications of impairment arise for a particular asset or group of assets, we assess the future recoverability\rof the carrying value of the asset (or asset group) based on an undiscounted cash flow analysis. If carrying value exceeds projected,\rnet, undiscounted cash flows, an additional analysis is performed to determine the fair value of the asset (or asset group), typically\ra discounted cash flow analysis, and an impairment charge is recorded for the excess of carrying value over fair value. Research\rand Development Research\rand development expenses include payroll, employee benefits, and other headcount-related expenses associated with product development.\rResearch and development expenses also include third-party development and programming costs, localization costs incurred to translate\rsoftware for international markets, and the amortization of purchased software code and services content. Such costs related to\rsoftware development are included in research and development expense until the point that technological feasibility is reached,\rwhich for our software products, is generally shortly before the products are put into service. Once technological feasibility\ris reached, such costs are capitalized and amortized to cost of revenue over the estimated lives of the products. Research and\rdevelopment expense is included as an operating expense. Basic\rand Diluted Net Loss per Common Share Basic\rand diluted net loss per share attributable to common stockholders is computed by dividing net loss attributable to common stockholders\rby the weighted average number of common shares outstanding during the period. Our potentially dilutive shares, which include\routstanding common stock warrants, have not been included in the computation of diluted net loss per share attributable to common\rstockholders for all periods presented, as the results would be antidilutive. Such potentially dilutive shares are excluded when\rthe effect would be to reduce net loss per share.  Risks\rand Uncertainties The\rCompany is subject to risks from, among other things, competition associated with the industry in general, other risks associated\rwith financing, liquidity requirements, rapidly changing customer requirements and technologies and limited operating history. Contingencies Certain\rconditions may exist as of the date the financial statements are issued, which may result in a loss to the Company but which will\ronly be resolved when one or more future events occur or fail to occur. The Company&#146;s management and legal counsel assess\rsuch contingent liabilities, and such assessment inherently involves judgment. In assessing loss contingencies related to legal\rproceedings that are pending against the Company or unasserted claims that may result in such proceedings, the Company&#146;s\rlegal counsel evaluates the perceived merits of any legal proceedings or unasserted claims as well as the perceived merits of\rthe amount of relief sought or expected to be sought. If\rthe assessment of a contingency indicates it is probable that a material loss has been incurred and the amount of the liability\rcan be estimated, then the estimated liability would be accrued in the Company&#146;s financial statements. If the assessment\rindicates that a potential material loss contingency is not probable but is reasonably possible, or is probable but cannot be\restimated, then the nature of the contingent liability, together with an estimate of the range of possible loss if determinable\rand material would be disclosed. Loss contingencies considered to be remote by management are generally not disclosed unless they\rinvolve guarantees, in which case the guarantee would be disclosed. Goodwill Goodwill\rrepresents the excess of the purchase price over the fair value of the net assets acquired in a business combination. Goodwill\ris not amortized but is evaluated for impairment at the reporting unit level annually as of December 31, or more frequently if\revents or changes in circumstances indicate that impairment may exist. Effective\rNovember 28, 2012, the Company adopted ASU 2011-08, which allows the Company to first assess qualitative factors to determine\rwhether it is more likely than not that the fair value of a reporting unit is less than its carrying value. This step serves as\rthe basis for determining whether it is necessary to perform the two-step goodwill impairment test. The two-step test first compares\rthe fair value of the reporting unit to its carrying value. If the fair value exceeds the carrying value, no impairment exists,\rand the second step is not performed. If the fair value is less than the carrying value, the second step is performed to compute\rthe amount of the impairment by comparing the implied fair value of reporting unit goodwill with the carrying amount of that goodwill.\rThe adoption did not have a material impact on the consolidated financial statements. The\rCompany evaluated its goodwill for impairment on December 31, 2014, and concluded there was no impairment as of that date. Recently\rIssued Accounting Pronouncements In\rAugust 2014, the FASB issued Accounting Standards Update No. 2014-15, Presentation of Financial Statements &#150; Going\rConcern (Subtopic 205-40), Disclosure of Uncertainties about an Entities Ability to Continue as a Going Concern(ASU 2014-15).\rThe guidance in ASU 2014-15 sets forth management&#146;s responsibility to evaluate whether there is substantial doubt about an\rentity&#146;s ability to continue as a going concern as well as required disclosures. ASU 2014-15 indicates that, when preparing\rfinancial statements for interim and annual financial statements, management should evaluate whether conditions or events, in\rthe aggregate, raise substantial doubt about the entity&#146;s ability to continue as a going concern for one year from the date\rthe financial statements are issued or are available to be issued. This evaluation should include consideration of conditions\rand events that are either known or are reasonably knowable at the date the financial statements are issued or are available to\rbe issued, as well as whether it is probable that management&#146;s plans to address the substantial doubt will be implemented\rand, if so, whether it is probable that the plans will alleviate the substantial doubt. ASU 2014-15 is effective for annual periods\rending after December 15, 2016, and interim periods and annual periods thereafter. Early application is permitted. The Company\ris currently in the process of evaluating the impact of adoption of this ASU on its consolidated financial statements. In\rJanuary 2015, the FASB issued Accounting Standards Update No. 2015-01, Income Statement &#150; Extraordinary and Unusual items\r(Subtopic 225-20), Simplifying Income Statement Presentation by Eliminating the Concept of Extraordinary Items (ASU 2015-01).\rThe amendment eliminates from U.S. GAAP the concept of extraordinary items. This guidance is effective for the Company in the\rfirst quarter of fiscal 2017. Early adoption is permitted and allows the Company to apply the amendment prospectively or retrospectively.\rThe adoption of this guidance is not expected to have a material impact on the Company&#146;s consolidated financial statements.'
