S'The financial statements\rof the Company have been prepared in accordance with accounting principles generally accepted in the United States (&#147;US GAAP&#148;)\rand are expressed in U.S. dollars. The Company&#146;s fiscal year end is November 30.The preparation of\rfinancial statements in conformity with US GAAP requires management to make estimates and assumptions that affect the reported\ramounts of assets and liabilities and disclosure of contingent assets and liabilities at the date of the financial statements and\rthe reported amounts of revenues and expenses during the reporting period. The Company bases its estimates and assumptions on current\rfacts, historical experience and various other factors that it believes to be reasonable under the circumstances, the results of\rwhich form the basis for making judgments about the carrying values of assets and liabilities and the accrual of costs and expenses\rthat are not readily apparent from other sources. The actual results experienced by the Company may differ materially and adversely\rfrom the Company&#146;s estimates. To the extent there are material differences between the estimates and the actual results, future\rresults of operations will be affected.The Company considers\rall highly liquid instruments with a maturity of three months or less at the time of issuance to be cash equivalents. As of November\r30, 2013 and 2012, there were no cash equivalents.c)In accordance with\rASC 360, &#147;Property Plant and Equipment&#148;, the Company tests long-lived assets or asset groups for recoverability\rwhen events or changes in circumstances indicate that their carrying amount may not be recoverable. Circumstances which could trigger\ra review include, but are not limited to: significant decreases in the market price of the asset; significant adverse changes in\rthe business climate or legal factors; accumulation of costs significantly in excess of the amount originally expected for the\racquisition or construction of the asset; current period cash flow or operating losses combined with a history of losses or a forecast\rof continuing losses associated with the use of the asset; and current expectation that the asset will more likely than not be\rsold or disposed significantly before the end of its estimated useful life. Recoverability is assessed based on the carrying amount\rof the asset and its fair value which is generally determined based on the sum of the undiscounted cash flows expected to result\rfrom the use and the eventual disposal of the asset, as well as specific appraisal in certain instances. An impairment loss is\rrecognized when the carrying amount is not recoverable and exceeds fair value.The Company computes\rnet income (loss) per share in accordance with ASC 260,Earnings per Share. ASC 260 requires presentation of both basic\rand diluted earnings per share (&#147;EPS&#148;) on the face of the income statement. Basic EPS is computed by dividing net income\r(loss) available to common shareholders (numerator) by the weighted average number of shares outstanding (denominator) during the\rperiod. Diluted EPS gives effect to all dilutive potential common shares outstanding during the period using the treasury stock\rmethod and convertible preferred stock using the if-converted method. In computing diluted EPS, the average stock price for the\rperiod is used in determining the number of shares assumed to be purchased from the exercise of stock options or warrants. Diluted\rEPS excludes all dilutive potential shares if their effect is anti-dilutive. During the twelve months ended November 30, 2013 and\r2012, the Company has no potentially dilutive debt or equity instruments issued or outstanding..  The Company accounts\rfor income taxes using the asset and liability method in accordance with ASC 740,Accounting for Income Taxes. The asset\rand liability method provides that deferred tax assets and liabilities are recognized for the expected future tax consequences\rof temporary differences between the financial reporting and tax bases of assets and liabilities, and for operating loss and tax\rcredit carryforwards. Deferred tax assets and liabilities are measured using the currently enacted tax rates and laws that will\rbe in effect when the differences are expected to reverse. The Company records a valuation allowance to reduce deferred tax assets\rto the amount that is believed more likely than not to be realized.ASC\r220,Comprehensive Income, establishes standards for the reporting and display of comprehensive loss and its components\rin the financial statements. During the twelve months ended November 30, 203 and 2012 our net loss was identical to our comprehensive\rloss.The\rCompany recognizes revenue from online advertising.  Revenue will be recognized only when the price is fixed and determinable,\rpersuasive evidence of an arrangement exists, the service has been provided, and collectability is assured.  The Company\ris not exposed to any credit risks as amounts are prepaid prior to performance of services.Pursuant to ASC 820,Fair Value Measurements and Disclosures, an entity is required to maximize the use of observable inputs and minimize the\ruse of unobservable inputs when measuring fair value. ASC 820 establishes a fair value hierarchy based on the level of independent,\robjective evidence surrounding the inputs used to measure fair value. A financial instrument&#146;s categorization within the fair\rvalue hierarchy is based upon the lowest level of input that is significant to the fair value measurement. ASC 820 prioritizes\rthe inputs into three levels that may be used to measure fair value:Level\r1Level 1 applies to\rassets or liabilities for which there are quoted prices in active markets for identical assets or liabilities.Level\r2Level 2 applies to\rassets or liabilities for which there are inputs other than quoted prices that are observable for the asset or liability such as\rquoted prices for similar assets or liabilities in active markets; quoted prices for identical assets or liabilities in markets\rwith insufficient volume or infrequent transactions (less active markets); or model-derived valuations in which significant inputs\rare observable or can be derived principally from, or corroborated by, observable market data.Level 3Level 3 applies to\rassets or liabilities for which there are unobservable inputs to the valuation methodology that are significant to the measurement\rof the fair value of the assets or liabilities.The Company&#146;s\rfinancial instruments consist principally of cash, accounts payable and accrued liabilities, and amounts due to related party.\rPursuant to ASC 820, the fair value of cash is determined based on &#147;Level 1&#148; inputs, which consist of quoted prices in\ractive markets for identical assets. The recorded values of all other financial instruments approximate their current fair values\rbecause of their nature and respective maturity dates or durations.The Company records\rstock-based compensation in accordance with ASC 718,Compensation &#150; Stock Compensationusing the fair value method.\rAll transactions in which goods or services are the consideration received for the issuance of equity instruments are accounted\rfor based on the fair value of the consideration received or the fair value of the equity instrument issued, whichever is more\rreliably measurable. Equity instruments issued to employees and the cost of the services received as consideration are measured\rand recognized based on the fair value of the equity instruments issued.  As at November 30, 2013 and 2012, the Company had\rnot grant any stock options. The Company has reviewed\rall the recently issued, but not yet effective, accounting pronouncements and does not believe that the future adoption of any\rsuch pronouncements may be expected to cause a material impact on its financial condition or the results of its operations as reported\rin its financial statements.Certain\rreclassifications have been made to the 2012 and March 15, 2010 (inception) to November 30, 2012 financial statements to conform\rto the 2013 presentation Advertising costs are\rexpensed as incurred. The Company recorded no advertising costs for during the twelve months ended November 30, 2013 or 2012.'
