S'2.SIGNIFICANT ACCOUNTING POLICIES Cash and Cash Equivalents Cash and cash equivalents include cash and\rhighly liquid investments with original maturities of three months or less when purchased. Allowance for Doubtful Accounts The Company records its allowance for doubtful\raccounts based upon its assessment of various factors. The Company considers historical experience, the age of the accounts receivable\rbalances, credit quality of the Company&#146;s customers, current economic conditions and other factors that may affect customers&#146;\rability to pay. Inventory Inventory is stated at the lower of cost or\rmarket and cost is determined using the first-in, first-out method. Inventory is primarily comprised of finished goods. As of December\r31, 2015, the majority of our inventory related to Government and Commercial Identity products for intended near-term sales. Long-Lived Assets and Impairment of Long-Lived\rAssets The Company&#146;s long-lived assets include\rproperty and equipment, goodwill and intangible assets. The Company reviews its long-lived assets for\rimpairment whenever events or changes in circumstances indicate that the carrying amount of these assets may not be fully recoverable\rin accordance with ASC topic 350 and ASC Topic 360 to determine recoverability of its long-lived assets, the Company evaluates\rthe probability that future undiscounted net cash flows, without interest charges, will be less than the carrying amount of the\rassets. Impairment is measured at fair value. Property and Equipment Property and equipment are recorded at cost\rand are depreciated over their estimated useful lives ranging from three to ten-years using the straight-line method. Leasehold\rimprovements are amortized utilizing the straight-line method over the lesser of the term of the lease or estimated useful life\rof the asset. Goodwill Goodwill represents the excess of acquisition\rcost over the fair value of net assets acquired in business combinations. Pursuant to ASC Topic 350, the Company tests goodwill\rfor impairment on an annual basis in the fourth quarter, or between annual tests, in certain circumstances. Under guidance, the\rCompany first assessed qualitative factors to determine whether it was necessary to perform the two-step quantitative goodwill\rimpairment test. An entity is not required to calculate the fair value of a reporting unit unless the entity determines, based\ron a qualitative assessment, that it is more likely than not that its fair value is less than its carrying amount. Events or changes\rin circumstances which could trigger an impairment review include macroeconomic conditions, industry and market conditions, cost\rfactors, overall financial performance, other entity specific events and sustained decrease in share price. The Company performed its annual impairment\rtest of goodwill in the fourth quarter for the years ended December 31, 2015 and 2014. For the year ended December 31, 2015, the\rCompany determined no impairment charge was required. For the year ended December 31, 2014, the Company recognized an impairment\rcharge of $4,207,000. See Note 5 for further details. Intangible Assets Intangible assets include trade names, patents,\rdeveloped technology and non-contractual customer relationships as described more fully in Note 5. The Company uses the straight\rline method to amortize these assets over their estimated useful lives. The Company reviews its long-lived assets for impairment\rwhenever events or changes in circumstances indicate that the carrying amount of these assets may not be fully recoverable in accordance\rwith ASC Topic 360. To determine recoverability of its long-lived assets, the Company evaluates the probability that future undiscounted\rnet cash flows, without interest charges, will be less than the carrying amount of the assets. Impairment is measured at fair value.\rNo impairments were recognized during the years ended December 31, 2015 and 2014. Deferred Rent The Company received certain rent abatements\rand incentives from landlord as an inducement to move into its New York office facility. The Company is amortizing these incentives\ron a straight line basis over the period of its respective lease. Revenue Recognition and Deferred Revenue Revenue is generally recognized when persuasive\revidence of an arrangement exists, delivery has occurred, the fee is fixed and determinable, collectability is probable, and there\ris no future Company involvement or commitment. The Company sells its commercial products directly through its sales force and\rthrough distributors. Revenue from directsales of products is recognized when shipped to the customer and title has passed. Under the provisions of ASC Topic 605-25, &#147;Revenue\rArrangements with Multiple Deliverables,&#148; for multi-element arrangements that include tangible products containing software\ressential to the tangible product&#146;s functionality and undelivered software elements relating to the tangible product&#146;s\ressential software, the Company allocates revenue to all deliverables based on their relative selling prices. In such circumstances,\rthe Company uses a hierarchy to determine the selling price to be used for allocating revenue to deliverables: (i) vendor-specific\robjective evidence of fair value (&#147;VSOE&#148;), (ii) third-party evidence of selling price and (iii) best estimate of the\rselling price (&#147;ESP&#148;). VSOE generally exists only when the Company sells the deliverable separately and is the price\ractually charged by the Company for that deliverable. ESPs reflect the Company&#146;s best estimates of what the selling prices\rof elements would be if they were sold regularly on a stand-alone basis. The Company also recognizes revenues from licensing\rof its patented software to customers. The licensed software requires continuing service or post contractual customer support and\rperformance; accordingly, a portion of the revenue is deferred based on its fair value and recognized ratably over the period in\rwhich the future service, support and performance are provided, which is generally one to three years. Royalties from the licensing\rof the Company&#146;s technology are recognized as revenues in the period they are earned. Revenue from research and development contracts\rare generally with government agencies under long-term cost-plus fixed-fee contracts, where revenue is based on time and material\rcosts incurred. Revenue from these arrangements is recognized as time is spent on the contract and materials are purchased. Research\rand development costs are expensed as incurred. The Company also performs consulting work for\rother companies. These services are billed based on time and materials. Revenue from these arrangements is also recognized as time\ris spent on the contract and materials are purchased. Subscriptions to database information can be\rpurchased for month-to-month, one, two, and three year periods. Revenue from subscriptions are deferred and recognized over the\rcontractual period, which is typically three years. The Company offers enhanced extended warranties\rfor its sales of hardware and software at a set price. The revenue from these sales are deferred and recognized on a straight-line\rbasis over the contractual period, which is typically one to three years. Research and Development Costs Research and development costs are charged\rto expense as incurred. Shipping Costs The Company&#146;s shipping and handling costs\rare included in cost of revenues for all periods presented. Income Taxes The Company accounts for income taxes\runder in accordance with ASC Topic 740, &#147;Accounting for Income Taxes.&#148; Deferred tax assets and liabilities are recognized\rfor the estimated future tax consequences attributable to differences between the financial statement carrying amounts of existing\rassets and liabilities and their respective tax bases and net operating loss carryforwards. Deferred tax assets and liabilities\rare measured using expected tax rates in effect for the year in which those temporary differences are expected to be recovered\ror settled. Deferred tax assets are recognized subject to management&#146;s judgment that realization is more likely than not.\rThe Company has recorded a full valuation allowance for its net deferred tax assets as of December 31, 2015 and 2014, due to the\runcertainty of the realizability of those assets. Fair Value of Financial Instruments The Company adheres to the provisions of ASC\rTopic 820, &#147;Fair Value Measurements and Disclosures&#148;. This pronouncement requires that the Company calculate the fair\rvalue of financial instruments and include this additional information in the notes to financial statements when the fair value\ris different than the book value of those financial instruments. The Company&#146;s financial instruments include cash and cash\requivalents, accounts receivable, note receivable, accounts payable and accrued expenses. At December 31, 2015 and 2014, the carrying\rvalue of the Company&#146;s financial instruments approximated fair value, due to their short-term nature. Business Concentration and Credit Risk Financial instruments, which subject the Company\rto concentrations of credit risk, consist primarily of cash and cash equivalents. The Company maintains cash with one financial\rinstitution. The cash equivalents consist of money market funds. The Company performs periodic evaluations of the relative credit\rstanding of these institutions. The Company&#146;s sales are principally made\rto large retail customers, financial institutions concentrated in the United States of America and to U.S. government entities.\rThe Company performs ongoing credit evaluations, generally does not require collateral, and establishes an allowance for doubtful\raccounts based upon factors surrounding the credit risk of customers, historical trends and other information. During the year ended December 31, 2015, the\rCompany had one customer that accounted for 31% of revenue. The revenue was associated with a commercial identity sales customer.\rThis customer represented 11% of total accounts receivable at December 31, 2015. During the year ended December 31, 2014 the Company\rdid not have any single customer account for 10% of revenue. At December 31, 2014, the Company had five customers whose accounts\rreceivable exceeded 10% of accounts receivable and represented 54% of total accounts receivable at December 31, 2014. As of December 31, 2015, the Company had three\rsuppliers for the production of its input devices. The Company has modified its software to operate in windows based systems and\rcan integrate with different hardware platforms that are readily available in the marketplace. The Company does not maintain a\rmanufacturing facility of its own and is not dependent on maintaining its production relationships due to the flexibility of its\rsoftware to run on multiple existing platforms. Net Loss and Net Loss Per Share Basic net loss per share is computed by dividing\rthe net loss for the period by the weighted average number of common shares outstanding during the period. Diluted net loss per\rshare is computed by dividing the net loss for the period by the weighted average number of shares of common stock and potentially\rdilutive common stock outstanding during the period. The dilutive effect of outstanding options and restricted stock is reflected\rin diluted earnings per share by application of the treasury stock method. The calculation of diluted net loss per share excludes\rall anti-dilutive shares.  The following table summarizes the common\rstock equivalents excluded from loss per diluted share because their effect would be anti-dilutive:  Share Based Compensation The Company accounts for the issuance\rof equity awards to employees in accordance ASC Topic 715 and 505, which requires that the cost resulting from all share based\rpayment transactions be recognized in the financial statements. This pronouncement establishes fair value as the measurement objective\rin accounting for share based payment arrangements and requires all companies to apply a fair value based measurement method in\raccounting for all share based payment transactions with employees. Period compensation costs are included in selling, general\rand administrative and research and development expenses. The Company recognizes compensation\rexpense related to stock option grants on a straight-line basis over the vesting period. Comprehensive Loss The Company&#146;s comprehensive loss\ris equal to its net loss for the years ended December 31, 2015 and 2014. Segment Information The Company adheres to the provisions\rof ASC Topic 280, which establishes standards for the way public business enterprises report information about operating segments\rin annual financial statements and requires that those enterprises report selected information about operating segments in financial\rstatements issued to shareholders. Management has determined that it has only one reporting segment. Use of Estimates The preparation of the Company&#146;s financial\rstatements in conformity with accounting principles generally accepted in the United States of America requires management to make\restimates and assumptions that affect the amounts reported in the Company&#146;s financial statements and accompanying notes.\rSignificant estimates and assumptions that affect amounts reported in the financial statements include impairment of goodwill and\rintangible assets, deferred tax valuation allowances, allowances for doubtful accounts, revenue allocation of multi-element arrangements\rand the fair value of options granted under the Company&#146;s share based compensation plans. Due to the inherent uncertainties\rinvolved in making estimates, actual results reported in future periods may be different from those estimates. Recent Accounting Pronouncements Not Yet\rEffective In May 2014, the Financial Accounting Standards\rBoard (&#147;FASB&#148;) issued Accounting Standards Update (&#147;ASU&#148;) 2014-09,&#147;Revenue from Contracts with\rCustomers (Topic 606).&#148; ASU 2014-09 completes the joint effort by the FASB and International Accounting Standards Board\r(&#147;IASB&#148;) to improve financial reporting by creating common revenue recognition guidance for U.S. GAAP and International\rFinancial Reporting Standards (&#147;IFRS&#148;). ASU 2014-09 applies to all companies that enter into contracts with customers\rto transfer goods or services. ASU 2014-09 is effective for public entities for interim and annual reporting periods beginning\rin the first quarter of 2018. Early adoption is permitted beginning in the first quarter of 2017 for public companies. . The Company\ris currently evaluating the requirements of ASU 2014-09 and have not yet determined its impact on our consolidated financial statements. In August 2014, the FASB issued ASU No. 2014-15,Presentation of Financial Statements &#150; Going Concern (Subtopic 205-40): Disclosure of Uncertainties about an Entity&#146;s\rAbility to Continue as a Going Concern(&#147;ASU 2014-15&#148;) which defines management&#146;s responsibility to evaluate,\rat each annual and interim reporting period, whether there are conditions or events that raise substantial doubt about an entity&#146;s\rability to continue as a going concern within one year after the date the financial statements are issued and to provide related\rfootnote disclosures in certain circumstances. In connection with each annual and interim period, management must assess if there\ris substantial doubt about the company&#146;s ability to continue as a going concern within one year after the issuance date.\rDisclosures are required if conditions give rise to substantial doubt. This standard is effective for all companies in the first\rannual period ending after December 15, 2016, and interim periods thereafter, with early adoption permitted. The Company is currently\revaluating the requirements of ASU 2014-15 and has not yet determined the impact on its consolidated financial statements. In July 2015, the FASB issued ASU No. 2015-11,Inventory(Topic 330): Simplifying the Measurement of Inventory(&#147;ASU 2015-11&#148;) which changes the measurement\rprinciple for inventory from the lower of cost or market to the lower of cost and net realizable value. ASU 2015-11 defines net\rrealizable value as estimated selling prices in the ordinary course of business, less reasonably predictable costs of completion,\rdisposal, and transportation. The new guidance must be applied on a prospective basis and is effective for periods beginning after\rDecember 15, 2016, with early adoption permitted. The Company is currently evaluating the effect that the new guidance will have\ron its financial statements and related disclosures. In November 2015, the FASB issued ASU No. 2015-17,Income Taxes(Topic 740):Balance Sheet Classification of Deferred Taxeswhich simplifies the presentation\rof deferred income taxes by eliminating the separate classification of deferred income tax liabilities and assets into current\rand noncurrent amounts in the consolidated balance sheet. The amendments in the update require that all deferred tax liabilities\rand assets be classified as noncurrent in the consolidated balance sheet. The amendments in this update are effective for annual\rperiods beginning after December 15, 2016, and interim periods therein and may be applied either prospectively or retrospectively\rto all periods presented. Early adoption is permitted. The Company is currently evaluating the impact this guidance is expected\rto have on its consolidated financial statements. In February 2016, the FASB issued ASU\rNo. 2016-02,Leases, which requires that lease arrangements longer than 12 months result in an entity recognizing an asset\rand liability. The pronouncement is effective for periods beginning after December 15, 2018 with early adoption permitted. The\rCompany is currently evaluating the impact this guidance is expected to have on its consolidated financial statements.'
