S"NOTE 2 - SUMMARY OF SIGNIFICANT ACCOUNTING\rPOLICIES Basis of presentation The Company&#146;s financial statements have\rbeen prepared in accordance with accounting principles generally accepted in the United States of America (&#147;U.S. GAAP&#148;).The\rpreparation offinancial statements\rinconformitywithaccounting principlesgenerally\racceptedintheUnited StatesofAmerica\rrequiresmanagementtomakeestimates\randassumptions\rthataffect\rthereported\ramountsof assetsandliabilities\randdisclosureofcontingent\rassetsandliabilitiesatthedateofthefinancial\rstatementsandthe reported\ramountsofrevenues\randexpensesduringthereporting\rperiod.\rActualresults\rcoulddifferfrom those estimates. Managementfurther\racknowledges\rthatitissolely responsibleforadoptingsound\raccounting practices,establishing andmaintainingasystem ofinternal accountingcontrolandpreventing\rand detectingfraud.TheCompany's\rsystem ofinternal\raccounting\rcontrolisdesignedtoassure,\ramong otheritems,that1)\rrecordedtransactions\rare valid;2) validtransactionsarerecorded;and3)transactions\rarerecorded\rintheproperperiod\rinatimelymannertoproduce financialstatementswhichpresentfairlythefinancial\rcondition,resultsofoperationsandcashflowsofthe\rCompany forthe\rrespectiveperiodsbeingpresented Development Stage Company The Company is a development stage company\ras defined by section 915-10-20 of the Financial Accounting Standards Board (&#147;FASB&#148;) Accounting Standards Codification\rfrom September 1, 2008 to present. The Company is still devoting substantially all of its efforts on establishing the business\rand, therefore, still qualifies as a development stage company. All losses accumulated since September 1, 2008 have been considered\ras part of the Company&#146;s development stage activities Use of estimates The preparation of financial statements in\rconformity with generally accepted accounting principles requires management to make estimates and assumptions that affect the\rreported amounts of assets and liabilities and disclosure of contingent assets and liabilities at the date of the financial statements\rand the reported amounts of revenues and expenses during the reporting period. Significant estimates include the estimated useful\rlives of property and equipment. Actual results could differ from those estimates. Cash equivalents The Company considers all highly liquid investments\rwith a maturity of three months or less when purchased to be cash equivalents. Fair value of financial instruments The Company follows paragraph 825-10-50-10\rof the FASB Accounting Standards Codification for disclosures about fair value of its financial instruments and paragraph 820-10-35-37\rof the FASB Accounting Standards Codification (&#147;Paragraph 820-10-35-37&#148;) to measure the fair value of its financial\rinstruments. Paragraph 820-10-35-37 establishes a framework for measuring fair value in accounting principles generally accepted\rin the United States of America (U.S. GAAP), and expands disclosures about fair value measurements. To increase consistency and\rcomparability in fair value measurements and related disclosures, Paragraph 820-10-35-37 establishes a fair value hierarchy which\rprioritizes the inputs to valuation techniques used to measure fair value into three (3) broad levels. The fair value hierarchy\rgives the highest priority to quoted prices (unadjusted) in active markets for identical assets or liabilities and the lowest priority\rto unobservable inputs. The three (3) levels of fair value hierarchy defined by Paragraph 820-10-35-37 are described below: The carrying amount of the Company&#146;s\rfinancial assets and liabilities, such as cash, prepaid expenses and accrued expenses approximate their fair value because of the\rshort maturity of those instruments. The Company&#146;s notes payable approximate the fair value of such instruments based upon\rmanagement&#146;s best estimate of interest rates that would be available to the Company for similar financial arrangements at\rMay 31, 2013. The Company does not have any assets or liabilities\rmeasured at fair value on a recurring or a non-recurring basis. Equipment Equipment is recorded at cost. Expenditures\rfor major additions and betterments are capitalized. Maintenance and repairs are charged to operations as incurred. Depreciation\rof equipment is computed by the straight-line method (after taking into account their respective estimated residual values) over\rthe assets estimated useful life of three (3) or seven (7) years. Upon sale or retirement of equipment, the related cost and accumulated\rdepreciation are removed from the accounts and any gain or loss is reflected in statements of operations. Impairment of long-lived assets The Company follows paragraph 360-10-05-4 of\rthe FASB Accounting Standards Codification for its long-lived assets. The Company&#146;s long-lived assets, which includes computer\requipment is reviewed for impairment whenever events or changes in circumstances indicate that the carrying amount of the asset\rmay not be recoverable. The Company assesses the recoverability of\rits long-lived assets by comparing the projected undiscounted net cash flows associated with the related long-lived asset or group\rof long-lived assets over their remaining estimated useful lives against their respective carrying amounts. Impairment, if any,\ris based on the excess of the carrying amount over the fair value of those assets. Fair value is generally determined using the\rasset&#146;s expected future discounted cash flows or market value, if readily determinable. If long-lived assets are determined\rto be recoverable, but the newly determined remaining estimated useful lives are shorter than originally estimated, the net book\rvalues of the long-lived assets are depreciated over the newly determined remaining estimated useful lives. The Company determined that there were no impairments\rof long-lived assets as of August 31, 2013. Commitments and contingencies The Company follows subtopic 450-20 of the\rFASB Accounting Standards Codification to report accounting for contingencies.  Liabilities for loss contingencies arising\rfrom claims, assessments, litigation, fines and penalties and other sources are recorded when it is probable that a liability has\rbeen incurred and the amount of the assessment can be reasonably estimated. Revenue recognition The Company follows paragraph 605-10-S99-1\rof the FASB Accounting Standards Codification for revenue recognition. The Company will recognize revenue when it is realized or\rrealizable and earned. The Company considers revenue realized or realizable and earned when all of the following criteria are met:\r(i) persuasive evidence of an arrangement exists, (ii) the product has been shipped or the services have been rendered to the customer,\r(iii) the sales price is fixed or determinable, and (iv) collectability is reasonably assured. Income taxes The Company follows Section 740-10-30 of the\rFASB Accounting Standards Codification, which requires recognition of deferred tax assets and liabilities for the expected future\rtax consequences of events that have been included in the financial statements or tax returns. Under this method, deferred tax\rassets and liabilities are based on the differences between the financial statement and tax bases of assets and liabilities using\renacted tax rates in effect for the fiscal year in which the differences are expected to reverse. Deferred tax assets are reduced\rby a valuation allowance to the extent management concludes it is more likely than not that the assets will not be realized. Deferred\rtax assets and liabilities are measured using enacted tax rates expected to apply to taxable income in the fiscal years in which\rthose temporary differences are expected to be recovered or settled. The effect on deferred tax assets and liabilities of a change\rin tax rates is recognized in the Statements of Income and Comprehensive Income in the period that includes the enactment date. The Company adopted section 740-10-25 of the\rFASB Accounting Standards Codification (&#147;Section 740-10-25&#148;) with regards to uncertainty income taxes. Section 740-10-25\raddresses the determination of whether tax benefits claimed or expected to be claimed on a tax return should be recorded in the\rfinancial statements. Under Section 740-10-25, the Company may recognize the tax benefit from an uncertain tax position only if\rit is more likely than not that the tax position will be sustained on examination by the taxing authorities, based on the technical\rmerits of the position. The tax benefits recognized in the financial statements from such a position should be measured based on\rthe largest benefit that has a greater than fifty percent (50%) likelihood of being realized upon ultimate settlement. Section\r740-10-25 also provides guidance on de-recognition, classification, interest and penalties on income taxes, accounting in interim\rperiods and requires increased disclosures. The Company had no material adjustments to its liabilities for unrecognized income\rtax benefits according to the provisions of Section 740-10-25. Net income (loss) per common share Net income (loss) per common share is computed\rpursuant to section 260-10-45 of the FASB Accounting Standards Codification. Basic net income (loss) per common share is computed\rby dividing net income (loss) by the weighted average number of shares of common stock outstanding during the period. Diluted net\rincome (loss) per common share is computed by dividing net income (loss) by the weighted average number of shares of common stock\rand potentially outstanding shares of common stock during the period. The weighted average number of common shares outstanding\rand potentially outstanding common shares assumes that the Company incorporated as of the beginning of the first period presented. There were no potentially dilutive shares outstanding\ras of August 31, 2013. Cash flows reporting The Company adopted paragraph 230-10-45-24\rof the FASB Accounting Standards Codification for cash flows reporting, classifies cash receipts and payments according to whether\rthey stem from operating, investing, or financing activities and provides definitions of each category, and uses the indirect or\rreconciliation method (&#147;Indirect method&#148;) as defined by paragraph 230-10-45-25 of the FASB Accounting Standards Codification\rto report net cash flow from operating activities by adjusting net income to reconcile it to net cash flow from operating activities\rby removing the effects of (a) all deferrals of past operating cash receipts and payments and all accruals of expected future operating\rcash receipts and payments and (b) all items that are included in net income that do not affect operating cash receipts and payments.  The\rCompany reports the reporting currency equivalent of foreign currency cash flows, using the current exchange rate at the time of\rthe cash flows and the effect of exchange rate changes on cash held in foreign currencies is reported as a separate item in the\rreconciliation of beginning and ending balances of cash and cash equivalents and separately provides information about investing\rand financing activities not resulting in cash receipts or payments in the period pursuant to paragraph 830-230-45-1 of the FASB\rAccounting Standards Codification. Advertising Costs The Company expenses the cost of advertising\rand promotional materials when incurred. Total Advertising costs were $0 for years ended August 31,2013 and 2012. Subsequent events The Company follows the guidance in Section\r855-10-50 of the FASB Accounting Standards Codification for the disclosure of subsequent events. The Company will evaluate subsequent\revents through the date when the financial statements were issued.  Pursuant to ASU 2010-09 of the FASB Accounting\rStandards Codification, the Company as an SEC filer considers its financial statements issued when they are widely distributed\rto users, such as through filing them on EDGAR. Recently issued accounting pronouncements The following accounting standards were\rissued as of December 26, 2011:"
