S'Principles\rof Consolidation&#150; The accompanying consolidated financial statements include the accounts of the Company. All significant\rintercompany balances and transactions have been eliminated in consolidation. Use\rof Estimates&#150; The preparation of consolidated financial statements in accordance with U.S. GAAP requires that management\rmake estimates and assumptions that affect the reported amounts of assets and liabilities and disclosure of contingent assets\rand liabilities at the date of the consolidated financial statements and the reported amounts of revenue and expenses during the\rreporting period. Management periodically assesses the accuracy of these estimates and assumptions. Actual results could differ\rfrom those estimates. Estimates are used when accounting for various items, including but not limited to allowances for doubtful\raccounts; net realizable value of inventory, derivative financial instruments; asset impairments; revenue recognition; depreciation\rand amortization; and other contingencies. Cash\rand Cash Equivalents -Cash balances in banks are insured by the Federal Deposit Insurance Corporation subject to certain\rlimitations.  For purposes of the statement of cash flows, the Company considers all highly liquid investments with a maturity\rof three months or less when purchased to be cash equivalents. Restricted\rCash- At June 30, 2014 and 2013, the Company had $72 and $0, respectively of restricted cash that was maintained at a blocked\rbank account created for the purpose of making payments, under agreements on a Promissory Note due to a third party manufacturer\r(see Note 9). Revenue\rRecognition&#150; Revenue is recognized when persuasive evidence of an arrangement exists, delivery has occurred or services\rhave been rendered, the fee is fixed and determinable and collectability is reasonably assured. The Company recognizes revenue\rwhen product is shipped or when it is received by the customer, depending on the contractual terms. The Company&#146;s revenue\ris comprised of the sale of its products to retailers and distributors. Allowance\rfor Doubtful Accounts&#150; The Company maintains an allowance for uncollectible accounts receivable for estimated losses\rresulting from the likelihood that customers will fail to make payments. Management determines the estimate of the allowance for\runcollectible accounts receivable by considering a number of factors, including: (1) historical experience; (2) aging\rof the accounts receivable; and (3) specific information obtained by the Company on the financial condition and the current\rcreditworthiness of its customers. Inventories&#150; Inventories are valued at the lower of cost or market. Cost is determined principally by the first-in, first-out method.\rThe costs of finished goods and work-in-process inventories include material, manufacturing labor and overhead components. The\rCompany periodically reviews the net realizable value of the inventory and, if necessary, records a reserve to reflect the net\rrealizable value of the inventory. Property\rand Equipment&#150; Property and equipment is stated at cost less accumulated depreciation. Depreciation of property and\requipment is provided using the straight-line method over the assets&#146; estimated useful lives. Leasehold improvements are\ramortized over the shorter of the assets&#146; economic lives or the lease term. Intangible\rAssets&#150; Intangible assets are carried at cost less accumulated amortization. For financial reporting purposes, amortization\rof intangibles has been computed over an estimated useful life of seven years using the straight-line method. Amortization expenses\rhave been included in operating expenses. Deferred\rRevenue&#150; Deferred revenue is comprised of all unearned revenue that has been collected in advance, primarily for future\roil well service, performance and appearance product purchases, and is recorded as deferred revenue on the balance sheet until\rthe revenue is earned. Impairment\rof Long-Lived Assets&#150; Long-lived assets are reviewed for impairment whenever events or changes in circumstances indicate\rthat the carrying amount of such assets may not be recoverable. When it becomes apparent that indicators such as a significant\rdecrease in the market value of the long-lived asset group or if material differences between operating results and the Company&#146;s\rforecasted expectations occur, then an impairment analysis is performed. If\rindicators arise, an initial determination of recoverability is performed based on an estimate of the undiscounted future cash\rflows resulting from the use of the asset and its eventual disposition compared with the carrying value. If the carrying value\rof the asset group exceeds the undiscounted cash flows, a measurement of an impairment loss for long-lived assets is performed.\rThe impairment charge is the excess of the carrying value of the asset group over the fair value, as determined utilizing appropriate\rvaluation techniques. Segments&#150; The Company has grouped its long-lived assets in accordance with the methodologies of how it manages the business.\rCurrently, the Company is one segment with multiple products, and as such the Company&#146;s asset group is based upon this one\rsegment methodology. Stock\rBased Compensation&#150; The Company accounts for stock-based awards to recipients in accordance with applicable accounting\rprinciples, which requires compensation expense related to share-based transactions, including employee stock options, to be measured\rand recognized in the financial statements based on a determination of the fair value of the stock options. The grant date fair\rvalue is determined using the Black-Scholes-Merton (&#147;Black-Scholes&#148;) pricing model. For all employee stock options,\rthe Company recognizes compensation expense over the requisite service period (generally, the vesting period of the stock-based\raward). The Company&#146;s option pricing model requires the input of highly subjective assumptions, including the expected stock\rprice volatility, expected term, and forfeiture rate. Any changes in these highly subjective assumptions could significantly impact\rstock-based compensation expense. Advertising\rand Promotional Costs&#150; Advertising and promotion costs, which are included in selling, general and administrative expense,\rare expensed as incurred.  During the years ended June 30, 2014 and 2013, advertising and promotion costs totaled $1,394\rand $2,965 respectively. Shipping\rCosts&#150; Shipping costs are included in selling, general and administrative expenses. During the years ended June 30,\r2014 and 2013, shipping cost totaled $149 and $349, respectively. Research\rand Development Costs&#150; Research and development costs, which are included in selling, general and administrative expense,\rconsist primarily of salaries and employment related expenses, independent testing fees and allocated facility costs. All such\rcosts are charged to expense as incurred.During the years ended June 30, 2014 and 2013, research\rand development costs totaled $319 and $557, respectively. Net\rLoss Per Share&#150; Basic net loss per share is based upon the weighted average number of common shares outstanding.  Diluted\rnet loss per share is based on the assumption that all dilutive convertible shares and stock options were converted or exercised.  Dilution\ris computed by applying the treasury stock method.  Under this method, options, warrants and restricted stock are assumed\rto be exercised at the beginning of the period (or at the time of issuance, if later), and as if funds obtained thereby were used\rto purchase common stock at the average market price during the period. Since the Company has incurred losses from all periods\rpresented, the dilutive per share calculation is the same as the basic calculation. Anti-dilutive securities not included in net\rloss per share calculation for the year include:  Income\rTaxes&#150; The Company accounts for income taxes by the recognition of deferred tax assets and liabilities for the expected\rfuture tax consequences of temporary differences between the recognition of tax effects for financial statement and income tax\rreporting purposes by applying enacted income tax rates applicable to future years to differences between the financial statement\rcarrying amounts and tax bases of existing assets and liabilities. A valuation allowance has been recorded to reduce net deferred\rtax assets to only that portion that is judged more likely than not to be realized. Fair\rValue Measurements&#150;Accounting standards have been issued which define fair value, establishes a market-based\rframework or hierarchy for measuring fair value and expands disclosures about fair value measurements. The standard is applicable\rwhenever another accounting pronouncement requires or permits assets and liabilities to be measured at fair value. The standard\rdoes not expand or require any new fair value measures; however its application may change current practice. Fair\rvalue is defined under the standard as the price that would be received to sell an asset or paid to transfer a liability in the\rprincipal or most advantageous market in an orderly transaction between market participants on the measurement date. The standard\ralso establishes a three-level hierarchy, which requires an entity to maximize the use of observable inputs and minimize the use\rof unobservable inputs when measuring fair value.    The\rCompany&#146;s financial instruments at June 30, 2014 consist of accounts receivable, accounts payable, notes payable and derivative\rliability. The Company believes the reported carrying amounts of its accounts receivable, accounts payable, derivative instruments\rand related party debt approximate fair value, based upon the short-term nature of these instruments.'
