S"Note 2. Summary\rof Significant Accounting Policies The summary of significant\raccounting policies presented below is designed to assist in understanding the Company&#146;s financial statements. Such financial\rstatements and accompanying notes are the representations of the Company&#146;s management, which is responsible for the integrity\rand objectivity. These accounting policies conform to accounting principles generally accepted in the United States of America\r(&#147;U.S. GAAP&#148;) in all material respects and have been consistently applied in preparing the accompanying financial statements. Basis of Presentation\rand Principles of Consolidation The consolidated financial\rstatements include the accounts of the Company, its wholly subsidiaries Z&#38;W CA and its majority owned subsidiaries JXZD. All\rinter-company transactions and balances were eliminated. The portion of the income applicable to non-controlling interests in subsidiary\rundertakings is reflected in the consolidated statements of operations. Use of Estimates\rand Assumptions The Company prepares\rits financial statements in conformity with U.S. GAAP, which requires management to make estimates and assumptions that affect\rthe reported amounts of assets and liabilities and disclosure of contingent assets and liabilities at the date of the financial\rstatements and the reported amounts of revenues and expenses during the reporting period. Actual results could differ from those\restimates. Foreign Currency\rAdjustments Assets and liabilities\rrecorded in foreign currencies are translated at the exchange rate on the balance sheet date. Revenue and expenses are translated\rat average rates of exchange prevailing during the year. Any translation adjustments are reflected as a separate component of stockholders&#146;\requity (deficit) and have no effect on current earnings. Gains and losses resulting from foreign currency transactions are included\rin current results of operations. During the years ended December 31, 2015 and 2014, the Company had aggregate\rforeign currency translation gain of $400,600 and $22,664, respectively. Cash and Cash Equivalents The Company considers\rall highly liquid investments purchased with an original maturity of three months or less to be cash equivalents. Accounts Receivable Accounts receivable\rare stated at the amount the Company expects to collect. The Company maintains allowances for doubtful accounts for estimated losses\rresulting from the inability of its customers to make required payments. Management considers the following factors when determining\rthe collectability of specific customer accounts: customer credit-worthiness, past transaction history with the customer, current\reconomic industry trends, and changes in customer payment terms. Past due balances over 90 days and other higher risk amounts are\rreviewed individually for collectability. If the financial condition of the Company&#146;s customers were to deteriorate, adversely\raffecting their ability to make payments, additional allowances would be required. Based on management&#146;s assessment, the\rCompany provides for estimated uncollectible amounts through a charge to earnings and a credit to a valuation allowance. Balances\rthat remain outstanding after the Company has used reasonable collection efforts are written off through a charge to the valuation\rallowance and a credit to accounts receivable. As of December 31, 2015 and 2014, the Company recorded allowances of $201,191 and\r$100,042, respectively, for doubtful accounts from certain sales that occurred but had not been collected. Inventories Finished goods, work-in-process,\rand raw materials are valued at the lower of average production cost and net realizable value. The Company records the costs of\rore stacked on its leach pads and in process at its production sites as heap leach ore and working process inventories measured\rat the lower of cost and estimated net realizable value in inventory. These costs are charged to earnings and included in cost\rof revenues on the basis of tons of precious mineral sold. The estimates and assumptions used in the measurement of heap leach\rore and work-in-process inventories include quantities of ore stacked on leach pads, recoverable tons of precious minerals contained\rin ore stacked on leach pads, recoverable tons of precious minerals in the mill processing circuits and the price expected to be\rrealized when the tons of precious minerals are recovered. If these estimates\ror assumptions prove to be inaccurate, the Company could be required to write down the carrying amounts of its heap leach ore and\rwork-in-process inventories, which would reduce the Company&#146;s earnings and working capital. Property and Equipment Property and equipment\ris stated at the historical cost, less accumulated depreciation. Depreciation on property, plant and equipment is provided using\rthe straight-line method over the estimated useful lives of the assets for both financial and income tax reporting purposes as\rfollows:  Expenditures for normal\rrepairs and maintenance are charged to expense as incurred.  Significant renewals and improvements are capitalized.  The\rcosts and related accumulated depreciation of assets retired or otherwise disposed of are eliminated from the accounts, and any\rresulting gain or loss is recognized in the year of disposal. Impairment of Long-Lived\rAssets Management reviews\rlong-lived assets for impairment whenever events or changes in circumstances indicate that the carrying amount may not be realizable\ror at a minimum annually during the fourth quarter of the year.  If an evaluation is required, the estimated future undiscounted\rcash flows associated with the asset are compared to the asset&#146;s carrying value to determine if an impairment of such asset\ris necessary.  The effect of any impairment would be to expense the difference between the fair value of such asset and\rits carrying value. Income Taxes An asset and liability\rapproach is used for financial accounting and reporting for income taxes. Deferred income taxes arise from temporary differences\rbetween income tax and financial reporting and principally relate to recognition of revenue and expenses in different periods for\rfinancial and tax accounting purposes and are measured using currently enacted tax rates and laws. In addition, a deferred tax\rasset can be generated by net operating loss carry forwards. If it is more likely than not that some portion or all of a deferred\rtax asset will not be realized, a valuation allowance is recognized. The Company has tax losses that may be applied against future\rtaxable income. The potential tax benefit arising from these loss carryforwards are offset by a valuation allowance due to uncertainty\rof profitable operations in the future. Fair Values of Financial\rInstruments Management believes\rthat the carrying amounts of the Company&#146;s financial instruments, consisting primarily of cash and accounts payable, approximated\rtheir fair values as of December 31, 2015 and 2014, due to their short-term nature. Non-controlling\rInterest Non-controlling interests\rin the Company&#146;s subsidiaries are reported as a component of equity, separate from the parent&#146;s equity. Purchase or\rsale of equity interests that do not result in a change of control are accounted for as equity transactions. Results of operations\rattributable to the minority interest are included in our consolidated results of operations and, upon loss of control, the interest\rsold, as well as interest retained, if any, will be reported at fair value with any gain or loss recognized in earnings. Revenue Recognition Revenue is recognized\rwhen products are shipped, title and risk of loss is passed to the customers and collection is reasonably assured. Payments received\rprior to the satisfaction of above criteria are recorded as deferred revenue. Basic and Diluted\rEarnings (Loss) Per Common Share The basic net loss\rper common share is computed by dividing the net loss by the weighted average number of common shares outstanding. Diluted net\rloss per common share is computed by dividing the net loss adjusted on an &#147;as converted&#148; basis, by the weighted average\rnumber of common shares outstanding plus potential dilutive securities. For all periods presented, there were no potentially dilutive\rsecurities outstanding. Subsequent Events The Company evaluated\revents subsequent to December 31, 2015 through the date the financial statements were issued for disclosure consideration. Recently Issued\rAccounting Pronouncements In April 2015, the\rFASB issued ASU No. 2015-03, Interest - Imputation of Interest (Subtopic 835-30): Simplifying the Presentation of Debt\rIssuance Costs (&#34;ASU 2015-03&#34;), which provides guidance on simplifying the presentation of debt issuance costs\ron the balance sheet. To simplify presentation of debt issuance costs, the amendments in ASU No. 2015-03 require that debt issuance\rcosts related to a recognized debt liability be presented in the balance sheet as a direct deduction from the carrying amount of\rthat debt liability, consistent with debt discounts. The recognition and measurement guidance for debt issuance costs are not affected\rby the amendments in this update. In August 2015, the FASB issued ASU No. 2015-15, Interest&#151;Imputation of Interest\r(Subtopic 835-30): Presentation and Subsequent Measurement of Debt Issuance Costs Associated with Line-of-Credit Arrangements&#151;Amendments\rto SEC Paragraphs Pursuant to Staff Announcement at June 18, 2015 EITF Meeting (SEC Update) (&#34;ASU 2015-15&#34;),\rto address the presentation or subsequent measurement of debt issuance costs related to line-of-credit arrangements. Under ASU\r2015-15, entities are permitted to defer and present debt issuance costs as an asset and subsequently amortize the deferred debt\rissuance costs ratably over the term of the line-of-credit arrangement, regardless of whether there are any outstanding borrowings\ron the line-of credit-arrangement. ASU 2015-03 and ASU 2015-15 are effective for annual reporting periods beginning after December\r15, 2015, including interim periods within that reporting period and early adoption is permitted for financial statements that\rhave not yet been previously issued. In accordance with ASU 2015-03 and ASU 2015-15, companies should apply the new guidance on\ra retrospective basis, wherein the balance sheet of each individual period presented should be adjusted to reflect the period-specific\reffects of applying the new guidance. Upon transition, an entity is required to comply with the applicable disclosures for a change\rin an accounting principle. The Company will adopt these pronouncements in the first quarter of 2016. Adoption is not expected\rto have a material effect on the Company's consolidated financial statements, but will affect balance sheet presentation. In April 2015, the\rFASB issued ASU 2015-03, &#147;Simplifying the Presentation of Debt Issuance Costs.&#148; ASU 2015-03 requires that debt issuance\rcosts related to a recognized debt liability be presented in the balance sheet as a direct deduction from the carrying amount of\rthat debt liability, consistent with debt discounts. The ASU is effective for annual periods beginning after December 15, 2015,\rand interim periods within those annual periods, early adoption is permitted. The Company is currently evaluating the effects of\rASU 2015-03 on the consolidated financial statements. In July 2015, the FASB\rissued ASU No. 2015-11, Inventory (Topic 330) - Simplifying the Measurement of Inventory (&#34;ASU 2015-11&#34;), which\rsimplifies the subsequent measurement of inventories by replacing the lower of cost or market test with a lower of cost and net\rrealizable value test. The guidance applies only to inventories for which cost is determined by methods other than last-in first-out\r(&#34;LIFO&#34;) and the retail inventory method. The guidance in ASU No. 2015-11 is effective for periods beginning after December\r15, 2016 and early adoption is permitted. The Company will adopt this pronouncement in the first quarter of 2017 and is currently\revaluating the impact, if any, adoption will have on its financial position and results of operations. In September 2015,\rthe FASB issued ASU No. 2015-16, Business Combinations (Topic 805): Simplifying the Accounting for Measurement Period Adjustments(&#34;ASU\r2015-16&#34;), as part of its simplification initiative. Under ASU 2015-16, an acquirer would be required to recognize adjustments\rto provisional amounts that are identified during the measurement period in the reporting period in which the adjustment amounts\rare determined. Further, the acquirer must record, in the financial statements for the same period, the effect on earnings of changes\rin depreciation, amortization, or other income effects, if any, as a result of the change to the provisional amounts, calculated\ras if the accounting had been completed at the acquisition date. Under ASU 2015-16, entities must also present separately on the\rface of the income statement or disclose in the notes the portion of the amount recorded in current period earnings by line item\rthat would have been recorded in previous reporting periods if the adjustment to the provisional amounts had been recognized as\rof the acquisition date. The guidance in ASU No. 2015-16 is effective for periods beginning after December 15, 2015 and should\rbe applied prospectively to adjustments to provisional amounts that occur after the effective date. Early adoption is permitted\rfor financial statements that have not been issued. The Company adopted this pronouncement in the third quarter of 2015 and\rthe adoption of this standard did not have a material effect on the Company's consolidated financial statements.In November 2015,\rthe FASB issued ASU 2015-17. ASU 2015-17 simplifies the classification of deferred income tax liabilities and assets on the\rbalance sheet by requiring deferred tax liabilities and assets to be classified as non-current on the balance sheet rather than\rclassifying them separately into current and non-current amounts. The guidance in ASU No. 2015-17 is effective for periods beginning\rafter December 15, 2016 and early adoption is permitted. The Company early adopted this pronouncement in the fourth quarter of\r2015 on a prospective basis. As a result, the Company has presented all deferred tax assets and liabilities as non-current on\rthe accompanying consolidated balance sheet as of December 31, 2015, but has not reclassified current deferred tax assets and\rliabilities on the accompanying consolidated balance sheet at December 31, 2014. See Note 8, &#147;Income Taxes&#148;,\rfor further information regarding the adoption of this standard. The Company\rdoes not believe that any other recently issued effective pronouncements, or pronouncements issued but not yet effective, if adopted,\rwould have a material effect on the accompanying financial statements."
